1
00:00:22,760 --> 00:00:24,512
[Band playing lively music]

2
00:00:33,840 --> 00:00:35,193
[Neighing]

3
00:00:37,800 --> 00:00:39,119
[Mooing]

4
00:00:56,440 --> 00:00:57,793
[Whooping]

5
00:01:43,120 --> 00:01:44,792
[People cheering]

6
00:01:50,920 --> 00:01:54,276
-What on earth is he doing?
-lt's called bulldogging, ma'am.

7
00:01:54,520 --> 00:01:57,159
That's Bulldog Burnett.
He works for my outfit.

8
00:01:58,680 --> 00:02:02,275
lt's a perfectly silly way
to handle cattle, if you ask me.

9
00:02:08,480 --> 00:02:09,993
My name is Charles Ellsworth.

10
00:02:10,320 --> 00:02:12,788
l can tell by your speech
that you're from England.

11
00:02:12,880 --> 00:02:15,235
May l ask what has brought you
to our fair shore?

12
00:02:15,520 --> 00:02:17,590
-A ship.
-Hilary.

13
00:02:17,960 --> 00:02:20,349
We brought some cattle over.
We're from Herefordshire.

14
00:02:20,440 --> 00:02:22,396
lf you'll excuse us, please.
Come along, Hilary.

15
00:02:22,480 --> 00:02:23,754
l know a countryman of yours.

16
00:02:23,840 --> 00:02:26,673
John Taylor. You should meet him.
He has a spread next to ours.

17
00:02:26,760 --> 00:02:27,954
He bested you again, Simons.

18
00:02:28,040 --> 00:02:29,439
Them critters Burnett draws...

19
00:02:29,520 --> 00:02:31,715
lay down and
roll over when they see him coming.

20
00:02:31,840 --> 00:02:34,354
Being's as how l probably bulldogged
their pas...

21
00:02:34,440 --> 00:02:35,953
they know what to expect.

22
00:02:36,280 --> 00:02:39,033
SAM: You're next, Sagamon.
SAGAMON: Right.

23
00:02:43,680 --> 00:02:45,352
GERT: Sam. Look who's here.

24
00:02:45,440 --> 00:02:47,635
Jeff, how are you? Hi, Gert.

25
00:02:48,280 --> 00:02:49,872
Jeff, it's been a long time.

26
00:02:49,960 --> 00:02:52,076
More than a year
since he caught that horn.

27
00:02:52,160 --> 00:02:53,832
But l ain't through
punching cows yet.

28
00:02:53,920 --> 00:02:55,239
Not by a long shot.

29
00:02:55,360 --> 00:02:57,032
Taylor said he took care of things.

30
00:02:57,120 --> 00:02:58,758
He promised a lot of things.

31
00:02:59,320 --> 00:03:02,551
All Jeff got was $40
and a ticket to St. Louis.

32
00:03:02,960 --> 00:03:06,270
Formerly of England,
and now from Texas, Mr. John Taylor.

33
00:03:06,600 --> 00:03:07,555
How do you do?

34
00:03:07,640 --> 00:03:10,313
Mr. Ellsworth tells me
you brought these Herefords over.

35
00:03:10,400 --> 00:03:13,312
lf Mr. Evans is about,
l'd like to talk to him about them.

36
00:03:13,400 --> 00:03:15,994
My husband was killed
in an accident aboard ship.

37
00:03:16,440 --> 00:03:17,793
l'm deeply sorry, ma'am.

38
00:03:17,880 --> 00:03:21,873
But it's indeed a blessing to find
someone at last who knows Herefords.

39
00:03:23,240 --> 00:03:25,959
MARTHA: They were bid in yesterday.
HlLARY: By a dairy farmer.

40
00:03:26,040 --> 00:03:28,235
What we were paid
hardly covered our transportation.

41
00:03:28,320 --> 00:03:30,356
MARTHA: Let's show them Vindicator, Hilary.

42
00:03:36,720 --> 00:03:37,675
[Bull grunts]

43
00:03:38,920 --> 00:03:42,230
lt's all right.
Vindicator's really very gentle.

44
00:03:42,960 --> 00:03:46,953
My daughter has a special affection
for Vindicator. She raised him.

45
00:03:47,360 --> 00:03:49,271
Are you going
to sell that bull, Mrs. Evans?

46
00:03:49,360 --> 00:03:51,112
l'm afraid l must.
We need the money.

47
00:03:51,200 --> 00:03:52,997
He'll be auctioned at noon today.

48
00:03:53,080 --> 00:03:55,833
You won't find much market
for that muley bull here.

49
00:03:55,920 --> 00:03:56,909
Muley?

50
00:03:57,280 --> 00:03:59,271
Why, your bull has no horns.

51
00:03:59,560 --> 00:04:01,232
<i>He's a freak in that respect.</i>

52
00:04:01,440 --> 00:04:06,230
Mr. Ellsworth, Vindicator's lack
of horns is a product of breeding...

53
00:04:06,320 --> 00:04:08,038
and it is not a freak condition.

54
00:04:08,120 --> 00:04:10,793
Please, ladies, l didn't intend
to start an argument.

55
00:04:11,040 --> 00:04:14,157
My partner Alex Bowen
raises the cattle and ships to me.

56
00:04:14,600 --> 00:04:16,238
<i>I'm in the packing end of the game.</i>

57
00:04:16,320 --> 00:04:18,231
l see. A butcher.

58
00:04:18,480 --> 00:04:20,072
Hilary, please.

59
00:04:20,520 --> 00:04:22,556
One morning you'll wake up
to a train whistle...

60
00:04:22,640 --> 00:04:24,995
and there won't be any more
cattle drives.

61
00:04:25,080 --> 00:04:27,548
Yes, sir, in a few years
it'll all be gone.

62
00:04:28,120 --> 00:04:29,519
Leastwise, the way we knew it.

63
00:04:29,600 --> 00:04:32,194
Don't start faulting what
you can't stand up to, Harter...

64
00:04:32,280 --> 00:04:33,474
just 'cause you're finished.

65
00:04:33,560 --> 00:04:36,154
l've still got a hoot and a holler
left in me.

66
00:04:36,240 --> 00:04:38,390
Sure. lf somebody buys you a bottle.

67
00:04:38,480 --> 00:04:39,833
SAM: Now wait a minute, Simons.

68
00:04:39,920 --> 00:04:43,310
Here's a man that broke most of
the trails you're riding today.

69
00:04:43,440 --> 00:04:47,194
Man?
All l see is a deadbeat on crutches.

70
00:04:47,560 --> 00:04:49,869
She's no better.
Watch your wallets, men.

71
00:04:49,960 --> 00:04:51,712
She'll put the bite on you for sure.

72
00:04:52,040 --> 00:04:54,076
[Lively instrumental music]

73
00:04:55,600 --> 00:04:57,033
Close the gate.

74
00:05:08,200 --> 00:05:09,758
[Lively instrumental music continues]

75
00:05:14,480 --> 00:05:17,870
-Mabry, get in there and stop them.
-Yes, sir.

76
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:26,752
Can't somebody put a stop to this?

77
00:05:26,840 --> 00:05:28,637
lt's all right, ma'am,
l'll protect you.

78
00:05:28,720 --> 00:05:31,951
Don't you worry about that bull.
l'll see that you get a good price.

79
00:05:32,120 --> 00:05:33,075
[Groaning]

80
00:05:38,440 --> 00:05:40,078
Here, get off my bull.

81
00:05:48,360 --> 00:05:49,918
Excuse me, ma'am.

82
00:05:52,760 --> 00:05:54,113
[All yelling]

83
00:05:58,600 --> 00:06:01,956
-Our bull is loose.
-Don't worry, ma'am, l'll get him.

84
00:06:02,400 --> 00:06:04,197
[Amusing instrumental music]

85
00:06:10,640 --> 00:06:12,039
[Bull bellowing]

86
00:06:16,040 --> 00:06:18,998
MAN: Missed the horns, Burnett.
WOMAN #1 : Slipped out from under him.

87
00:06:19,080 --> 00:06:20,638
WOMAN #2: He tried to dog a muley.

88
00:06:22,600 --> 00:06:23,555
[Whistles]

89
00:06:26,360 --> 00:06:28,191
SAM: Look out, miss,
he's headed this way.

90
00:06:28,280 --> 00:06:29,679
<i>Come on. Up you go.</i>

91
00:06:32,200 --> 00:06:34,589
You're the one
that has to be looked out for.

92
00:06:34,760 --> 00:06:36,273
What kind of a bull is that?

93
00:06:37,720 --> 00:06:39,676
[Whistles patriotic tune]

94
00:06:45,360 --> 00:06:47,078
Thank you, Mr. Burnett.

95
00:06:48,280 --> 00:06:49,474
You all right, Sam?

96
00:06:49,960 --> 00:06:51,439
Thanks, Gert.

97
00:06:51,680 --> 00:06:55,070
You can't bulldog
a bull that doesn't have any horns.

98
00:06:55,560 --> 00:06:58,711
l didn't break anything,
just chipped my pride, l guess.

99
00:06:58,800 --> 00:07:02,190
That seems to hurt worse
than anything, don't it, Sam?

100
00:07:03,080 --> 00:07:04,559
[All laughing]

101
00:07:06,440 --> 00:07:07,634
l'll kill Burnett.

102
00:07:07,960 --> 00:07:09,632
From now on, Mabry here is top hand.

103
00:07:09,720 --> 00:07:11,711
You'll take orders from him.

104
00:07:12,600 --> 00:07:15,512
You'll notice the hornless condition
being an innovation...

105
00:07:15,600 --> 00:07:18,512
that should meet with the approval
of each and every one...

106
00:07:18,600 --> 00:07:20,158
who must move or ship cattle.

107
00:07:20,240 --> 00:07:22,834
Mother, if that butcher bids,
l'll die.

108
00:07:23,560 --> 00:07:26,996
Now, really, Hilary
you must learn to trust people more.

109
00:07:27,080 --> 00:07:28,832
l had a long talk
with Mr. Ellsworth...

110
00:07:28,920 --> 00:07:31,832
and he assured me that he'll be
bidding for his partner in Texas.

111
00:07:31,920 --> 00:07:35,196
Mr. Bowen is extremely interested
in improving his stock.

112
00:07:35,520 --> 00:07:37,238
Now, who will start the bidding?

113
00:07:37,480 --> 00:07:38,708
$700.

114
00:07:39,080 --> 00:07:41,275
AUCTlONEER: $700 is bid
by Mr. Charles Ellsworth.

115
00:07:42,440 --> 00:07:43,873
<i>$800 by Mr. John TayIor.</i>

116
00:07:43,960 --> 00:07:45,916
$900 for the lovely ladies
from England.

117
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:47,558
lf she'd had an elephant up there...

118
00:07:47,640 --> 00:07:49,790
Ellsworth would have bid
on that, too.

119
00:07:50,120 --> 00:07:53,510
TAYLOR: $1,000.
AUCTlONEER: $1,000 from Taylor of Texas.

120
00:07:53,800 --> 00:07:54,994
$1,100.

121
00:07:55,440 --> 00:07:57,237
Don't go away, Sam,
l've got a job for you.

122
00:07:57,320 --> 00:07:59,788
Bowen doesn't want that muley bull.

123
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:04,152
$1,100 from Mr. Ellsworth on behalf
of Mr. Alex Bowen of Texas.

124
00:08:04,840 --> 00:08:07,354
-$1,200.
-$1,500.

125
00:08:07,720 --> 00:08:10,553
AUCTlONEER: $1,500 from that....
SAM: Have you lost your mind?

126
00:08:11,680 --> 00:08:12,829
$1,600.

127
00:08:12,920 --> 00:08:15,639
ELLSWORTH: $2,000.
AUCTlONEER: $2,000 is bid.

128
00:08:16,040 --> 00:08:18,315
<i>$</i>2,<i>000 once, $</i>2,<i>000 twice.</i>

129
00:08:18,920 --> 00:08:22,196
<i>SoId to Mr. CharIes EIIsworth</i>
<i>for $</i>2,<i>000.</i>

130
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:26,468
[Singing] <i>God save our gracious queen</i>

131
00:08:27,080 --> 00:08:29,071
AUCTlONEER: lf you will
kindly step forward...

132
00:08:29,160 --> 00:08:30,878
for your signatures
on the bill of sale.

133
00:08:30,960 --> 00:08:34,430
Get that bull on the Dodge City
train tonight and get it to Bowen.

134
00:08:34,520 --> 00:08:36,397
l'm not taking
that knob head anywhere.

135
00:08:36,480 --> 00:08:38,755
l'm working for Bowen, not you.

136
00:08:38,840 --> 00:08:41,035
You won't be working
for anyone if you keep talking.

137
00:08:41,120 --> 00:08:42,439
That suits me just fine.

138
00:08:42,520 --> 00:08:45,034
You get yourself another man.
l quit.

139
00:08:45,320 --> 00:08:47,072
There goes Bulldog Burnett.

140
00:08:47,480 --> 00:08:48,674
Just a cowpoke, miss.

141
00:08:48,880 --> 00:08:50,632
Long on muscle, short on brains.

142
00:08:50,920 --> 00:08:52,797
l'll get a good hand
to take Vindicator west.

143
00:08:52,880 --> 00:08:54,108
You can depend on that.

144
00:08:54,200 --> 00:08:55,997
l'm sure l can, Mr. Ellsworth.

145
00:08:56,080 --> 00:08:58,230
Suppose you drop
round the hotel this afternoon...

146
00:08:58,320 --> 00:08:59,639
and pick up your money.

147
00:09:00,120 --> 00:09:01,917
<i>I'm in Room</i> 22.

148
00:09:09,640 --> 00:09:11,437
l've got a business deal for you.

149
00:09:11,760 --> 00:09:14,513
Same kind of deal
you handed Jeff Harter?

150
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:17,956
l'll give you $500 for that bull.

151
00:09:18,040 --> 00:09:19,393
lt's not mine to sell.

152
00:09:19,840 --> 00:09:22,035
Bowen doesn't want it
and neither does Ellsworth.

153
00:09:22,120 --> 00:09:24,031
But l do,
and l'm willing to pay for it.

154
00:09:24,120 --> 00:09:26,588
Ellsworth paid $2,000 for it.

155
00:09:27,080 --> 00:09:29,958
l'm buying a bull,
not female companionship.

156
00:09:31,760 --> 00:09:34,320
All right, l'll go $1,000.

157
00:09:35,880 --> 00:09:38,758
l'll have Mabry and Simons
take the noon train to Dodge...

158
00:09:39,080 --> 00:09:40,672
and meet you there tomorrow.

159
00:09:41,160 --> 00:09:42,513
[Cow mooing]

160
00:09:47,480 --> 00:09:49,357
All right, l'll deliver it.

161
00:09:53,080 --> 00:09:54,354
[Soft instrumental music]

162
00:09:54,440 --> 00:09:55,509
[Knocking on door]

163
00:09:55,600 --> 00:09:57,238
Coming, dear lady.

164
00:10:02,200 --> 00:10:03,997
<i>What in thunder</i>
<i>do you want, Burnett?</i>

165
00:10:04,080 --> 00:10:06,913
ELLSWORTH: You quit.
SAM: l want to talk to you about that.

166
00:10:10,920 --> 00:10:12,035
Well, get to it.

167
00:10:12,120 --> 00:10:14,236
l've decided to deliver
that bull to Bowen.

168
00:10:14,640 --> 00:10:15,629
All right, fine.

169
00:10:15,720 --> 00:10:18,518
You get it out of town and
don't bother me about it anymore.

170
00:10:18,600 --> 00:10:22,115
Now look, Sam, be short, be polite,
and then be on your way.

171
00:10:24,080 --> 00:10:25,035
<i>WeIcome.</i>

172
00:10:25,120 --> 00:10:27,839
Mr. Burnett is just leaving
to put Vindicator on the train.

173
00:10:27,920 --> 00:10:28,909
Have a good trip, Sam.

174
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:31,878
MARTHA: Then you've changed your opinion
about Vindicator?

175
00:10:31,960 --> 00:10:33,029
Well, no, ma'am.

176
00:10:33,120 --> 00:10:36,271
l just thought l'd enjoy the trip
hearing them cattlemen laugh...

177
00:10:36,360 --> 00:10:38,510
about that animal
all the way to Dodge.

178
00:10:38,800 --> 00:10:40,995
l'm sure Mr. Bowen won't laugh.

179
00:10:41,320 --> 00:10:43,788
That bull is a thing
that might tickle him a good deal.

180
00:10:43,880 --> 00:10:46,269
ELLSWORTH: Give my regards to Bowen.
Have a good trip.

181
00:10:46,360 --> 00:10:48,191
And now, my dear Mrs. Evans...

182
00:10:48,280 --> 00:10:50,111
shall we conclude
our little business?

183
00:10:50,200 --> 00:10:51,758
This calls for champagne.

184
00:10:52,840 --> 00:10:54,353
Meatpacking Romeo.

185
00:10:57,720 --> 00:11:01,156
When that $2,000 is gone,
Martha, you can tap me for more.

186
00:11:01,480 --> 00:11:03,357
l'm going to lay St. Louis
at your feet.

187
00:11:04,280 --> 00:11:06,430
l'm afraid
there won't be time for that.

188
00:11:06,680 --> 00:11:09,274
You see, Hilary and l are leaving
for England tonight.

189
00:11:09,480 --> 00:11:10,993
ELLSWORTH: But you can't be serious.

190
00:11:11,080 --> 00:11:13,674
l can do a lot for you.
l already have.

191
00:11:14,120 --> 00:11:18,432
Mr. Ellsworth,
l realise that a woman alone...

192
00:11:18,520 --> 00:11:22,229
has to expect some nonsense
from the adventurous male...

193
00:11:22,320 --> 00:11:25,835
but l sold you a Hereford bull,
nothing more.

194
00:11:26,280 --> 00:11:28,669
l buy beef for 10 cents a pound.

195
00:11:29,040 --> 00:11:31,110
l know companionship comes higher.

196
00:11:31,560 --> 00:11:33,915
l'm giving you your money back.
There is no sale.

197
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:36,798
lt's too late for that.
l'm the legal owner of that bull.

198
00:11:36,880 --> 00:11:39,553
You said that Vindicator would be
delivered to your partner.

199
00:11:39,640 --> 00:11:41,073
That was the condition of the sale.

200
00:11:41,440 --> 00:11:43,476
You run out on me,
and your bull will end up...

201
00:11:43,560 --> 00:11:45,676
-on that table tomorrow night.
-He will not.

202
00:11:45,960 --> 00:11:50,397
Vindicator will be used for breeding
in Texas. l shall see to that.

203
00:11:52,360 --> 00:11:55,750
lt's getting around train time.
l still have to load that darn bull.

204
00:11:55,840 --> 00:11:58,035
-lt might take a little doing.
-Sure would.

205
00:12:01,280 --> 00:12:03,999
Here's a kind of a mash note.

206
00:12:04,320 --> 00:12:07,517
Don't let Jeff read it. l always did
try and steal his girl.

207
00:12:07,600 --> 00:12:09,272
l'll see you next year.

208
00:12:09,720 --> 00:12:10,948
Mash note?

209
00:12:11,560 --> 00:12:13,596
Why, Sam was always so woman-shy...

210
00:12:13,680 --> 00:12:16,069
it took a team
just to drag him into a dance.

211
00:12:16,440 --> 00:12:18,112
$1,000?

212
00:12:18,400 --> 00:12:19,753
[Train whistle blowing]

213
00:12:29,280 --> 00:12:31,919
Come on, you big, red,
no-horned brute, get up.

214
00:12:36,320 --> 00:12:37,992
Hello, Mr. Burnett.

215
00:12:39,800 --> 00:12:42,712
-Here now, there's been a mistake.
-A mistake?

216
00:12:42,800 --> 00:12:46,190
You're not supposed to be....
You're on the wrong train.

217
00:12:46,400 --> 00:12:48,868
-lt's going to Dodge City, isn't it?
-Yes, it's going--

218
00:12:48,960 --> 00:12:50,757
Then we're on the right train,
Mr. Burnett.

219
00:12:50,840 --> 00:12:53,593
We're going to the Bowen Ranch
with you and Vindicator.

220
00:12:53,680 --> 00:12:55,750
Well, that's just about
as crazy an idea...

221
00:12:55,840 --> 00:12:59,037
as you walking all the way up
here on top of this train.

222
00:13:00,320 --> 00:13:02,629
You just did that, didn't you?

223
00:13:03,280 --> 00:13:05,430
How are you getting along
with Vindicator?

224
00:13:05,520 --> 00:13:07,272
l'm not getting along
with him at all.

225
00:13:07,520 --> 00:13:11,308
He's a useless hunk of gristle, and
besides, he's lying on my blankets.

226
00:13:11,400 --> 00:13:13,436
Vindicator is not useless.

227
00:13:13,840 --> 00:13:17,230
He'll certainly improve those
scrubby old longhorns of yours.

228
00:13:17,320 --> 00:13:21,029
Why, he's so handsome, the cows will
fight to present themselves to him.

229
00:13:21,320 --> 00:13:23,515
Now, what kind of talk is that?

230
00:13:23,600 --> 00:13:26,034
What kind of a thing
is that for a young lady to say?

231
00:13:26,240 --> 00:13:28,629
The facts of life
are no mystery to me, Mr. Burnett.

232
00:13:28,720 --> 00:13:31,109
After all,
l am a cattle breeder's daughter.

233
00:13:31,360 --> 00:13:33,555
You ought to be ashamed of yourself.

234
00:13:33,840 --> 00:13:36,479
My father taught me
to talk about such things.

235
00:13:36,560 --> 00:13:39,518
Bloodlines and breeding
were decent topics in our house.

236
00:13:39,800 --> 00:13:42,553
Nobody said anything
about your father.

237
00:13:42,640 --> 00:13:46,269
l was just.... What's the idea,
crashing in here on me like this?

238
00:13:46,360 --> 00:13:48,237
There's nothing sacred
about a cattle car.

239
00:13:48,320 --> 00:13:50,550
This one happens to be my bedroom.

240
00:13:50,640 --> 00:13:52,790
And you have not been invited
in here.

241
00:13:53,080 --> 00:13:56,390
Now, come on, you bison belly,
l'm gonna teach you how to behave.

242
00:13:56,480 --> 00:13:57,390
Come on, get up.

243
00:13:57,480 --> 00:13:59,948
Don't you dare kick
a helpless animal.

244
00:14:00,160 --> 00:14:02,799
And Vindicator doesn't appreciate
name-calling, either.

245
00:14:02,880 --> 00:14:04,313
You mean l've hurt his feelings?

246
00:14:04,400 --> 00:14:06,072
HlLARY: l mean Vindicator's lineage...

247
00:14:06,160 --> 00:14:08,071
is traceable back to James l.

248
00:14:08,480 --> 00:14:10,994
Which is a great deal
better than you can do, l'm sure.

249
00:14:11,080 --> 00:14:13,275
Why, he's practically royalty.

250
00:14:13,600 --> 00:14:16,398
And you might as well learn
how to handle him properly.

251
00:14:16,480 --> 00:14:18,072
Listen to me, if you please.

252
00:14:18,480 --> 00:14:20,118
[Whistles patriotic tune]

253
00:14:20,920 --> 00:14:21,875
[Mooing]

254
00:14:24,960 --> 00:14:26,188
There you are.

255
00:14:26,280 --> 00:14:27,759
Now you may try it, Mr. Burnett.

256
00:14:27,840 --> 00:14:30,115
<i>-God Save the Queen.</i>
-Now, hold on.

257
00:14:30,200 --> 00:14:31,758
l have my rights.

258
00:14:31,960 --> 00:14:36,272
l'm not gonna whistle a tune
for any royal, James l, muley bull.

259
00:14:36,440 --> 00:14:38,829
Now, you get back up
this ladder here.

260
00:14:39,080 --> 00:14:42,072
SAM: l'll help you.
HlLARY: l don't need your help, thank you.

261
00:14:42,160 --> 00:14:44,151
The female is no less agile
than the male.

262
00:14:44,240 --> 00:14:45,992
That's right, young lady. Goodbye.

263
00:14:49,880 --> 00:14:51,552
[Train whistle blowing]

264
00:14:56,040 --> 00:14:58,156
[Dramatic instrumental music]

265
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:09,433
[Screaming]

266
00:15:18,080 --> 00:15:19,195
Holy Moses.

267
00:15:20,280 --> 00:15:23,875
Come on, get down off here,
before you fall and break your neck.

268
00:15:24,800 --> 00:15:26,791
[Soft instrumental music]

269
00:15:30,800 --> 00:15:32,438
Careful now.

270
00:15:38,720 --> 00:15:40,551
[Train whistle blowing]

271
00:15:52,440 --> 00:15:56,319
PORTER: Mrs. Evans, your berths are ready.
MARTHA: Thank you.

272
00:15:56,560 --> 00:15:57,913
There's Mr. Burnett.

273
00:15:59,880 --> 00:16:01,154
Run along to bed, Hilary.

274
00:16:01,240 --> 00:16:03,037
l want to have a talk
with Mr. Burnett.

275
00:16:03,120 --> 00:16:04,758
You're wasting your time, Mother.

276
00:16:04,840 --> 00:16:08,037
He's obstinate, ill-tempered,
and quite lacking in education.

277
00:16:08,120 --> 00:16:10,918
Perhaps. But he does
have a rough intelligence...

278
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:13,639
which could be refined,
don't you think?

279
00:16:13,720 --> 00:16:15,551
Don't be long, Mother.

280
00:16:16,480 --> 00:16:19,313
Now, really, Mr. Burnett,
l don't bite.

281
00:16:21,560 --> 00:16:24,199
-Man overboard.
-Hold it, ma'am.

282
00:16:26,160 --> 00:16:28,628
Mr. Burnett, l am sorry.

283
00:16:28,720 --> 00:16:30,597
<i>But I thought</i>
<i>you'd faIIen over the raiIing.</i>

284
00:16:30,680 --> 00:16:33,353
No, ma'am.
l might jump, l'd never fall.

285
00:16:35,600 --> 00:16:37,033
Of course.

286
00:16:37,600 --> 00:16:39,955
Now, Mr. Burnett,
since we're travelling together...

287
00:16:40,040 --> 00:16:41,792
l see no point
in our avoiding each other.

288
00:16:41,880 --> 00:16:43,871
-There are many arrangements--
-Firstly...

289
00:16:43,960 --> 00:16:46,679
we're not travelling together.
We're just on the same train.

290
00:16:46,760 --> 00:16:48,637
And if l was you, l'd get off.

291
00:16:48,720 --> 00:16:52,030
l intend to deliver Vindicator
personally to Mr. Bowen.

292
00:16:52,120 --> 00:16:55,999
l'm doing that for Ellsworth,
and you don't figure in it at all.

293
00:16:56,080 --> 00:16:59,516
Now, my advice to you is to get
the first train back to St. Louis...

294
00:16:59,600 --> 00:17:02,433
and then get on home,
where you belong.

295
00:17:02,520 --> 00:17:05,637
Mr. Burnett,
you may bulldog a steer...

296
00:17:05,880 --> 00:17:07,996
but you cannot bulldog me.

297
00:17:08,280 --> 00:17:11,158
Vindicator represents generations
of selective breeding...

298
00:17:11,240 --> 00:17:12,992
and l intend to see
he's properly placed.

299
00:17:13,080 --> 00:17:14,115
Now, please, ma'am.

300
00:17:14,200 --> 00:17:16,509
l've had all the breeding
l can take for one day.

301
00:17:16,600 --> 00:17:20,798
The thing l'm trying to get over to
you is that this trip's dangerous.

302
00:17:20,880 --> 00:17:24,111
There's no telling
what might happen to you in Dodge.

303
00:17:24,200 --> 00:17:27,158
Surely our lives
will be safe in your hands.

304
00:17:27,240 --> 00:17:30,869
l don't want your lives in my hands.
l've got enough trouble with my own.

305
00:17:30,960 --> 00:17:33,315
The thing for you to do
is turn back at Dodge...

306
00:17:33,440 --> 00:17:37,069
and trust me to deliver
that bull of yours.

307
00:17:37,600 --> 00:17:41,434
Mr. Burnett, you will either act
as our guide to the Bowen Ranch...

308
00:17:41,520 --> 00:17:43,590
or l will get someone else.

309
00:17:44,080 --> 00:17:45,672
Good night, sir.

310
00:17:51,920 --> 00:17:54,036
[Soft instrumental music]

311
00:18:10,880 --> 00:18:12,438
[Bell clanging]

312
00:18:24,640 --> 00:18:26,915
Would you get our baggage, please?

313
00:18:36,880 --> 00:18:39,394
-ls there something wrong?
-Why, no, ma'am.

314
00:18:45,400 --> 00:18:47,436
SlMONS: Come on, you stupid....

315
00:18:47,520 --> 00:18:49,636
You fellows are gonna wreck
this whole deal.

316
00:18:49,720 --> 00:18:52,393
You don't know these two women
l've got on my neck.

317
00:18:52,600 --> 00:18:55,717
They're bound and determined to come
with me the whole way to Bowen's.

318
00:18:55,800 --> 00:18:59,429
They got paid $2,000 for this bull,
so they're out of it. Come on.

319
00:18:59,520 --> 00:19:01,750
You horn in now,
they'll call the Sheriff.

320
00:19:02,040 --> 00:19:03,678
SlMONS: You horn in, l'll call him.

321
00:19:03,760 --> 00:19:05,034
<i>You made a deaI with TayIor.</i>

322
00:19:05,120 --> 00:19:06,439
Now hold on, both of you.

323
00:19:06,520 --> 00:19:08,476
This whole thing is shady
all the way around.

324
00:19:08,560 --> 00:19:10,471
All l want is the bull.

325
00:19:10,680 --> 00:19:12,193
And you'll get it.

326
00:19:12,280 --> 00:19:14,840
l'll meet you over at the saloon.
We'll work something out.

327
00:19:14,920 --> 00:19:16,751
All right. Come on, Simons.

328
00:19:17,120 --> 00:19:20,908
All right. But don't make me have to
come looking for you, Burnett.

329
00:19:21,280 --> 00:19:23,714
Give me 20 minutes, l'll be there.

330
00:19:23,920 --> 00:19:25,831
<i>Now, come on, you, move.</i>

331
00:19:26,680 --> 00:19:30,434
<i>You muIey, red rump roast. Come on.</i>

332
00:19:30,800 --> 00:19:33,155
HlLARY: All you have to do is whistle,
Mr. Burnett.

333
00:19:33,840 --> 00:19:37,515
SAM: What are you doing here?
HlLARY: l thought you might need help.

334
00:19:37,680 --> 00:19:39,318
But l see you've had some.

335
00:19:40,640 --> 00:19:42,756
[Amusing instrumental music]

336
00:19:46,600 --> 00:19:48,750
[Sam whistles patriotic tune]

337
00:19:51,440 --> 00:19:53,271
Why, that's excellent, Mr. Burnett.

338
00:19:53,360 --> 00:19:55,271
You've learned
to handle him very well.

339
00:19:55,360 --> 00:19:58,511
Vindicator, you're a fickle-hearted
muley bull.

340
00:19:59,160 --> 00:20:01,958
l'm afraid Hilary is jealous,
Mr. Burnett.

341
00:20:02,400 --> 00:20:04,197
How soon can we be on our way?

342
00:20:04,280 --> 00:20:07,989
l've got to get a wagon and
all sorts of supplies and horses.

343
00:20:08,080 --> 00:20:10,275
Yes, of course.
But that won't take very long.

344
00:20:10,360 --> 00:20:12,954
l've asked the baggage man
to take our things to the hotel.

345
00:20:13,040 --> 00:20:14,632
So we'll wait there for you.

346
00:20:14,960 --> 00:20:19,317
Ma'am, l don't think you ought
to be so dead set on this trip.

347
00:20:19,760 --> 00:20:21,876
But l am dead set.

348
00:20:22,280 --> 00:20:24,794
So let's not waste the day in talk.

349
00:20:30,760 --> 00:20:32,955
[Cheerful instrumental music]

350
00:20:38,240 --> 00:20:41,391
HlLARY: ...one of them say
it was a shady deal all round.

351
00:20:41,720 --> 00:20:44,837
-Mother, you haven't been listening.
-Of course l have, dear.

352
00:20:44,920 --> 00:20:46,478
HlLARY: We should go to the Sheriff...

353
00:20:46,560 --> 00:20:48,790
and have Mr. Burnett thrown
into the hoosegow.

354
00:20:49,080 --> 00:20:53,039
-The what?
-The jail, jug, old Bailey.

355
00:20:53,560 --> 00:20:55,516
Why on earth should we do
a thing like that?

356
00:20:55,600 --> 00:20:57,750
Because they plan
to kidnap Vindicator...

357
00:20:57,840 --> 00:20:59,671
and Mr. Burnett
is in cahoots with them.

358
00:20:59,760 --> 00:21:02,991
What is this cahoots?
lt sounds awful.

359
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:08,993
Conspiracy. Anyway,
he said he'd meet them in the pub.

360
00:21:09,280 --> 00:21:11,510
lt has something to do
with that Mr. Taylor.

361
00:21:11,840 --> 00:21:14,400
Hilary, Mr. Taylor is an Englishman.

362
00:21:15,160 --> 00:21:17,754
So was Captain Kidd. Come on.

363
00:21:18,680 --> 00:21:20,591
lf we can find them, l'll show you.

364
00:21:21,320 --> 00:21:23,117
[Music playing]

365
00:21:23,840 --> 00:21:26,400
SAM: Wait a minute, Simons,
you go out on that street...

366
00:21:26,480 --> 00:21:27,799
and we'll all go to jail.

367
00:21:27,880 --> 00:21:29,074
Give us another drink.

368
00:21:29,160 --> 00:21:30,878
l don't want your whisky.
Come on, Mabry.

369
00:21:30,960 --> 00:21:33,190
l'm not letting those women
ride away with that bull.

370
00:21:33,280 --> 00:21:35,236
We're going straight through
Taylor's place.

371
00:21:35,320 --> 00:21:37,276
l'll stake that bull
out at Sand Creek.

372
00:21:37,360 --> 00:21:39,954
You come in at night and take him,
l'll say he strayed off.

373
00:21:40,040 --> 00:21:41,871
You're just gonna stir things
up here.

374
00:21:41,960 --> 00:21:43,313
You bet l am.

375
00:21:50,400 --> 00:21:52,152
You two women go over to the wagon.

376
00:21:52,240 --> 00:21:55,038
l've got a little business
to attend to here.

377
00:21:55,200 --> 00:21:57,236
l'll be with you directly.

378
00:22:08,840 --> 00:22:11,035
Does that look
like a conspiracy to you?

379
00:22:11,680 --> 00:22:13,193
The thieves have fallen out.

380
00:22:16,000 --> 00:22:18,639
l'm giving the orders here, Simons.
l said, quit it.

381
00:22:56,840 --> 00:22:57,795
[Screaming]

382
00:23:03,000 --> 00:23:04,433
Just look at that.

383
00:23:04,800 --> 00:23:06,074
[Women screaming]

384
00:23:11,800 --> 00:23:13,279
Those ruffians.

385
00:23:18,280 --> 00:23:21,750
Stop this at once.
This is too much. Drop that gun.

386
00:23:22,640 --> 00:23:24,676
How dare you hit that man.

387
00:23:25,520 --> 00:23:26,794
He was gonna shoot me.

388
00:23:26,880 --> 00:23:30,395
Now, really, Mr. Burnett, you have
a predisposition to violence...

389
00:23:30,480 --> 00:23:32,948
-of which l heartily disapprove.
-Yes, ma'am.

390
00:23:33,040 --> 00:23:35,998
Now, let's be on our way
before you cause more trouble.

391
00:23:36,080 --> 00:23:37,672
-Yes, ma'am.
-Come along, Hilary.

392
00:23:39,320 --> 00:23:41,311
[Amusing instrumental music]

393
00:23:41,600 --> 00:23:44,068
SAM: Excuse me, ma'am, you're on my hat.

394
00:23:46,000 --> 00:23:48,798
l see what
you're up against, all right.

395
00:23:49,080 --> 00:23:52,470
Sand Creek, day after tomorrow.
And that bull better be there.

396
00:24:05,200 --> 00:24:07,839
Very well, Mr. Burnett,
if you are ready.

397
00:24:07,920 --> 00:24:10,753
That horse is
a little hard to handle, ma'am.

398
00:24:10,840 --> 00:24:13,593
<i>If you can't ride</i>,
<i>maybe you'd better stay here.</i>

399
00:24:13,680 --> 00:24:16,558
We have ridden on occasion,
Mr. Burnett.

400
00:24:16,960 --> 00:24:18,439
<i>Haven't we, HiIary?</i>

401
00:24:19,640 --> 00:24:20,914
[Neighing]

402
00:24:23,320 --> 00:24:25,675
[Adventurous instrumental music]

403
00:24:35,040 --> 00:24:36,393
Just one thing, ma'am...

404
00:24:36,640 --> 00:24:38,870
if you're dead set
on making this trip to Texas...

405
00:24:38,960 --> 00:24:41,030
you're going the wrong way.

406
00:24:42,280 --> 00:24:43,679
Thank you, Mr. Burnett.

407
00:24:43,840 --> 00:24:47,594
-You are a very capable guide.
-l can tell north from south.

408
00:24:47,680 --> 00:24:49,113
Now, if you'll just....

409
00:25:00,880 --> 00:25:02,279
[Martha laughing]

410
00:25:04,080 --> 00:25:05,274
SAM: Where you been, ma'am?

411
00:25:05,360 --> 00:25:06,952
<i>I was about to go out</i>
<i>and Iook for you.</i>

412
00:25:07,040 --> 00:25:10,476
The only thing l concede
is that you had the better horse.

413
00:25:10,560 --> 00:25:12,710
SAM: We'll swap off and do it again.

414
00:25:16,200 --> 00:25:17,713
Thank you, Sam.

415
00:25:18,360 --> 00:25:20,430
Hilary, would you like to ride
a little while?

416
00:25:20,520 --> 00:25:22,317
No, thank you, Mother.

417
00:25:29,120 --> 00:25:30,599
l'll just drive along...

418
00:25:30,880 --> 00:25:33,713
just drive while you two consort.

419
00:25:34,160 --> 00:25:37,755
Really, Hilary, do you call
an innocent canter consorting?

420
00:25:37,920 --> 00:25:40,718
No, but l call
a half-a-day gallop a romp.

421
00:25:42,120 --> 00:25:44,156
[Amusing instrumental music]

422
00:25:53,520 --> 00:25:55,556
[Serene instrumental music]

423
00:25:59,720 --> 00:26:03,190
MARTHA: What do you think now,
Mr. Burnett, of Vindicator's ability to travel?

424
00:26:03,280 --> 00:26:04,679
He's doing all right.

425
00:26:04,800 --> 00:26:07,234
As well as a longhorn,
would you say?

426
00:26:07,320 --> 00:26:08,639
lt's hard to say.

427
00:26:08,840 --> 00:26:12,435
ln winter, the cattle have to travel
a good bit looking for feed...

428
00:26:12,520 --> 00:26:15,193
and in summers, every once
in a while there's a drought.

429
00:26:15,280 --> 00:26:18,636
A few wells and catch basins
would solve that problem.

430
00:26:19,040 --> 00:26:20,996
Alex Bowen's not gonna change...

431
00:26:21,080 --> 00:26:23,036
the countryside
to accommodate one bull.

432
00:26:23,120 --> 00:26:25,315
Mr. Bowen cannot stop progress.

433
00:26:26,520 --> 00:26:27,839
One day this whole range...

434
00:26:27,920 --> 00:26:30,229
will be occupied by
white-faced Hereford cattle.

435
00:26:30,560 --> 00:26:32,357
You'll see it happen.

436
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:45,754
SAM: l hung onto his horns,
and that fool steer ran a mile...

437
00:26:45,880 --> 00:26:48,519
me flapping like laundry
in a high wind.

438
00:26:48,600 --> 00:26:52,149
Finally, he stopped,
and looked at me real sorrowful...

439
00:26:52,480 --> 00:26:55,233
and then he just flopped down,
disgusted.

440
00:26:57,880 --> 00:26:59,677
And you were only 16?

441
00:27:00,200 --> 00:27:03,670
And from that time on,
they took to calling me Bulldog.

442
00:27:04,000 --> 00:27:07,709
From what l saw, things don't seem
to have changed very much.

443
00:27:07,840 --> 00:27:09,478
Here, l'll get you some more coffee.

444
00:27:09,920 --> 00:27:10,989
[Gunshots firing]

445
00:27:11,840 --> 00:27:13,398
[Tense instrumental music]

446
00:27:14,880 --> 00:27:16,791
-You all right?
-Yes, and you?

447
00:27:16,880 --> 00:27:19,838
lf anyone's interested,
Vindicator and l are all right, too.

448
00:27:19,960 --> 00:27:21,359
Must've been a stray shot.

449
00:27:21,480 --> 00:27:24,950
Funny that a stray shot should
just happen to hit our coffee pot.

450
00:27:25,040 --> 00:27:28,749
Now, Miss Hilary, don't start
dreaming up any more trouble.

451
00:27:29,320 --> 00:27:31,072
l think we'd better all turn in.

452
00:27:31,160 --> 00:27:33,435
Got to be up before daybreak.
Come on.

453
00:27:33,520 --> 00:27:35,670
l'll take care of Vindicator.

454
00:27:44,280 --> 00:27:45,713
[Whistles patriotic tune]

455
00:27:45,800 --> 00:27:46,710
[Bull mooing]

456
00:27:58,400 --> 00:27:59,753
Did you fire that shot?

457
00:27:59,840 --> 00:28:02,229
l was just reminding Burnett
to show up at Sand Creek.

458
00:28:02,320 --> 00:28:05,118
l told you once,
and l'm telling you again...

459
00:28:05,200 --> 00:28:06,474
l'll handle this.

460
00:28:07,080 --> 00:28:10,038
Mabry, out here
you ain't telling me nothing.

461
00:28:34,200 --> 00:28:35,269
HlLARY: There's your saddle.

462
00:28:35,360 --> 00:28:37,476
-Thank you. Your mother up?
-No.

463
00:28:37,560 --> 00:28:40,233
l just thought l'd help you
on your way.

464
00:28:40,600 --> 00:28:42,113
What's gotten into you now?

465
00:28:42,560 --> 00:28:43,993
Come now.

466
00:28:44,080 --> 00:28:46,435
That shot was a signal
from Taylor's men.

467
00:28:46,560 --> 00:28:48,278
You're taking Vindicator to them.

468
00:28:48,760 --> 00:28:50,671
<i>Go on, and good riddance.</i>

469
00:28:50,800 --> 00:28:53,075
You're dead wrong.
l was just gonna get you up.

470
00:28:53,760 --> 00:28:55,034
HlLARY: l just bet you were.

471
00:28:55,120 --> 00:28:56,599
l was and l am.

472
00:28:57,880 --> 00:29:00,474
Time to get up, ma'am.
Come on, roust out.

473
00:29:01,600 --> 00:29:03,591
HlLARY: lf you have any decency, you'll go.

474
00:29:03,680 --> 00:29:05,591
Vindicator will be better off
with Taylor...

475
00:29:05,680 --> 00:29:08,319
and my mother can certainly
do without you.

476
00:29:08,400 --> 00:29:11,995
-Hilary. What on earth--
-l know what you're up to.

477
00:29:12,080 --> 00:29:14,799
You've decided to play
Mr. Ellsworth's game.

478
00:29:14,880 --> 00:29:16,632
<i>Mr. Burnett is just Iike him.</i>

479
00:29:16,800 --> 00:29:20,315
-He certainly is not like him.
-No?

480
00:29:21,240 --> 00:29:23,879
One was willing to buy a bull
he didn't want...

481
00:29:23,960 --> 00:29:27,475
the other to sell one he didn't own.
lt's just the same.

482
00:29:27,560 --> 00:29:29,516
<i>OnIy this time, you don't care.</i>

483
00:29:29,600 --> 00:29:32,433
You can't see it
because you don't want to.

484
00:29:33,680 --> 00:29:35,989
Sam, is there any truth in this?

485
00:29:36,760 --> 00:29:39,149
Mother, l know what l heard.

486
00:29:40,240 --> 00:29:43,198
l'm just telling you
l got up to get an early start.

487
00:29:43,280 --> 00:29:46,875
What you heard in Dodge
doesn't have anything to do with us.

488
00:29:46,960 --> 00:29:48,598
You're calling me a liar.

489
00:29:48,680 --> 00:29:51,114
l'm just saying
that you misunderstood something...

490
00:29:51,200 --> 00:29:53,111
and imagined more.

491
00:29:53,280 --> 00:29:54,872
l suppose l only imagine...

492
00:29:55,120 --> 00:29:57,714
that you're trying to win
my mother's affections?

493
00:29:57,800 --> 00:30:00,872
Hilary, that question
is most certainly not to the point.

494
00:30:00,960 --> 00:30:03,190
lt's the whole point, Mother.

495
00:30:03,720 --> 00:30:05,756
<i>And Mr. Burnett knows it.</i>

496
00:30:12,920 --> 00:30:16,515
Vindicator is
going to be delivered to Alex Bowen.

497
00:30:16,680 --> 00:30:19,797
And the sooner we move,
the sooner we'll get there.

498
00:30:19,960 --> 00:30:22,235
Very well, Sam. Let's move.

499
00:30:23,680 --> 00:30:25,671
[Sober instrumental music]

500
00:30:43,360 --> 00:30:46,716
SAM: All right, hold up.
Give me the axe behind the seat.

501
00:30:51,400 --> 00:30:52,389
Wire.

502
00:30:53,280 --> 00:30:55,396
They'll wire the whole world.

503
00:30:55,960 --> 00:30:57,313
Telegraph wire...

504
00:30:59,920 --> 00:31:00,909
barbed wire.

505
00:31:01,720 --> 00:31:03,950
This must be private property.

506
00:31:04,080 --> 00:31:06,878
There's always been free passage
across this range.

507
00:31:06,960 --> 00:31:10,589
Taylor may own these sections,
he's got no right to wire them.

508
00:31:10,680 --> 00:31:13,114
Do you mean that we're going
onto Taylor's ranch?

509
00:31:13,200 --> 00:31:14,679
We're leaving it.

510
00:31:14,800 --> 00:31:17,030
<i>AII right, Martha</i>,
<i>bring the wagon through.</i>

511
00:31:17,120 --> 00:31:20,157
SAM: Let's make time.
MARTHA: Are you satisfied now, Hilary?

512
00:31:20,920 --> 00:31:21,909
l am.

513
00:31:56,840 --> 00:31:59,479
They ought to be moving
into Bosquo Canyon about now.

514
00:31:59,560 --> 00:32:02,393
Burnett had no intention of stopping
at Sand Creek.

515
00:32:02,680 --> 00:32:03,999
We better go tell Taylor.

516
00:32:04,080 --> 00:32:05,991
SlMONS: You're all through telling, Mabry.

517
00:32:06,200 --> 00:32:08,156
There's $3,000 waiting for me
in that canyon.

518
00:32:08,240 --> 00:32:09,992
lt'll get me all the way to Mexico.

519
00:32:10,440 --> 00:32:12,431
You're getting off right here.

520
00:32:12,840 --> 00:32:15,718
You're crazy, Simons.
Put that gun away.

521
00:32:16,240 --> 00:32:17,229
Start running.

522
00:32:17,440 --> 00:32:19,510
[Tense instrumental music]

523
00:32:34,600 --> 00:32:36,556
-Mother.
-Yes?

524
00:32:37,000 --> 00:32:39,673
-May l ride with you for a bit?
-Of course, dear.

525
00:32:48,920 --> 00:32:50,319
SAM: Better keep moving along.

526
00:32:50,400 --> 00:32:53,073
Few more miles
and we'll be out of this.

527
00:32:58,880 --> 00:33:00,950
Cattle up in there.

528
00:33:01,040 --> 00:33:02,109
[Horns clacking together]

529
00:33:02,200 --> 00:33:03,838
MARTHA: What's that noise?
SAM: Horns.

530
00:33:04,080 --> 00:33:05,069
Horns?

531
00:33:06,320 --> 00:33:07,309
Cattle horns.

532
00:33:08,120 --> 00:33:10,918
l'll be right back,
you follow along slow.

533
00:33:27,840 --> 00:33:29,068
[Cattle mooing]

534
00:33:34,960 --> 00:33:36,473
-Hi, Jamie.
-Hi, Sam.

535
00:33:36,680 --> 00:33:38,989
-Where are you moving the stock?
-To Dodge.

536
00:33:39,120 --> 00:33:41,918
l'm gonna cash them in
and be my own boss.

537
00:33:42,160 --> 00:33:43,673
Bowen know about this?

538
00:33:45,000 --> 00:33:47,673
Pa might miss the cattle
but he won't miss me.

539
00:33:47,760 --> 00:33:49,830
l figure he owes me something
for my time.

540
00:33:49,960 --> 00:33:51,029
You all alone?

541
00:33:51,120 --> 00:33:53,554
No, Felipe's back there
pushing the drag.

542
00:33:53,680 --> 00:33:55,033
Don't crowd them too much.

543
00:33:55,120 --> 00:33:57,873
-l got some people up ahead here.
-Right.

544
00:34:21,160 --> 00:34:23,116
[Tense instrumental music]

545
00:35:11,880 --> 00:35:12,949
[Horse neighing]

546
00:35:13,040 --> 00:35:14,758
[Dramatic instrumental music]

547
00:35:14,880 --> 00:35:16,313
[Yelling]

548
00:35:23,480 --> 00:35:25,550
Swing out! They're moving!

549
00:35:28,160 --> 00:35:29,115
[Gunshots firing]

550
00:35:44,480 --> 00:35:46,869
[Dramatic instrumental music continues]

551
00:35:52,680 --> 00:35:53,908
Come on.

552
00:36:06,160 --> 00:36:07,593
Turn that wagon around.

553
00:36:10,240 --> 00:36:11,912
[Yelling continues]

554
00:36:35,360 --> 00:36:36,475
[Hilary screams]

555
00:36:45,840 --> 00:36:48,070
Stay where you are. Get back.

556
00:37:04,760 --> 00:37:05,715
[Gun firing]

557
00:37:26,840 --> 00:37:29,308
[lntense instrumental music]

558
00:38:05,800 --> 00:38:07,438
Drop your gun right there.

559
00:38:19,480 --> 00:38:22,278
Now l'll take the money
Taylor paid you for the bull.

560
00:38:27,760 --> 00:38:29,079
l haven't got it.

561
00:38:29,160 --> 00:38:32,596
l'll search your corpse
if that's the way you want it.

562
00:38:33,920 --> 00:38:36,115
There'll be no need for that.

563
00:38:37,080 --> 00:38:38,991
l'll give you the money.

564
00:38:55,640 --> 00:38:58,279
How much were you paid
for Vindicator, Mr. Burnett?

565
00:38:58,360 --> 00:39:00,032
SlMONS: $1,000.

566
00:39:01,440 --> 00:39:03,396
[Tense instrumental music]

567
00:39:06,400 --> 00:39:07,799
<i>I'II take aII the money.</i>

568
00:39:11,360 --> 00:39:12,873
What else you got in there?

569
00:39:14,560 --> 00:39:15,515
[Gunshots firing]

570
00:39:17,800 --> 00:39:19,916
[Dramatic instrumental music]

571
00:39:34,680 --> 00:39:36,830
Stop it. Do you hear me? Stop it!

572
00:39:36,920 --> 00:39:38,353
<i>No wonder there's nothing out here.</i>

573
00:39:38,440 --> 00:39:40,112
<i>You're aII too busy</i>
<i>kiIIing each other.</i>

574
00:39:40,200 --> 00:39:43,909
Now, Mr. Simons,
l came by my $2,000 honestly...

575
00:39:44,000 --> 00:39:45,752
so you will please
give them back to me.

576
00:39:45,840 --> 00:39:47,114
<i>And then get out of here.</i>

577
00:39:47,200 --> 00:39:48,872
Look out, Martha,
he's still got a gun.

578
00:39:48,960 --> 00:39:50,234
So have l.

579
00:39:53,400 --> 00:39:56,039
No, please. Let him go.
l don't want any killing.

580
00:39:59,400 --> 00:40:00,674
[Gunshots firing]

581
00:40:11,720 --> 00:40:13,358
SlMONS: Come on. Get up.

582
00:40:17,760 --> 00:40:18,988
[Yelling]

583
00:40:28,440 --> 00:40:29,589
[Horse neighing]

584
00:41:22,000 --> 00:41:24,673
-You killed him.
-He didn't give me any choice.

585
00:41:26,040 --> 00:41:29,077
A man is dead, and this boy is hurt.

586
00:41:30,720 --> 00:41:32,995
All because of your dishonesty.

587
00:41:34,720 --> 00:41:37,234
That's one way to see it, ma'am.

588
00:42:04,080 --> 00:42:06,036
[Soft instrumental music]

589
00:42:21,120 --> 00:42:23,076
Out. There's the answer.

590
00:42:23,440 --> 00:42:25,237
Take what's due and skin out.

591
00:42:26,480 --> 00:42:28,311
HlLARY: Mother, can't we stop?

592
00:42:28,480 --> 00:42:30,118
lt isn't much farther, dear...

593
00:42:30,400 --> 00:42:32,038
and there'll be people there
to look after him.

594
00:42:33,280 --> 00:42:35,316
-You'll be home soon.
-Home?

595
00:42:35,400 --> 00:42:37,391
No. Where's my hat?

596
00:42:40,480 --> 00:42:42,869
[Sweeping instrumental music]

597
00:43:10,080 --> 00:43:11,672
[People chattering]

598
00:43:12,280 --> 00:43:15,113
Estaban. Juan.
Get Jamie inside, he's hurt.

599
00:43:19,400 --> 00:43:21,550
Please, lift him carefully.

600
00:43:43,080 --> 00:43:44,957
Here's Jamie, Alex. He's hurt.

601
00:43:45,440 --> 00:43:47,635
Aye, it doesn't surprise me.

602
00:43:47,920 --> 00:43:49,353
Felipe comes stumbling in...

603
00:43:49,440 --> 00:43:52,318
this afternoon
with a hole in his shoulder.

604
00:43:52,400 --> 00:43:53,310
[Snorting]

605
00:43:54,640 --> 00:43:56,312
Stampede, he says.

606
00:43:59,960 --> 00:44:03,714
MARTHA: Do you mean you knew your son
was in danger and didn't send help?

607
00:44:04,480 --> 00:44:08,519
Madam, l knew he'd either
make it back alive or he would not.

608
00:44:09,480 --> 00:44:12,199
ln this part of the world,
a helping hand comes too late.

609
00:44:12,280 --> 00:44:13,713
<i>Now, what do you want?</i>

610
00:44:14,160 --> 00:44:15,275
What do l want?

611
00:44:15,640 --> 00:44:17,278
Now, you listen to me.

612
00:44:17,680 --> 00:44:18,954
Your son is hurt.

613
00:44:19,160 --> 00:44:23,278
<i>And I want him moved to a warm room.</i>
<i>And then bring me some bandages.</i>

614
00:44:24,160 --> 00:44:25,878
You shut your gob, woman.

615
00:44:26,560 --> 00:44:29,120
Out here it's Alexander Bowen
what gives the orders...

616
00:44:29,200 --> 00:44:32,112
and you womenfolk listen
to what l say. ls that clear to you?

617
00:44:34,040 --> 00:44:36,474
You pompous, foul-smelling tyrant.

618
00:44:36,720 --> 00:44:39,632
l want that boy moved
where he can be looked after.

619
00:44:40,000 --> 00:44:42,230
Now, you and you there. Pick him up.

620
00:44:42,320 --> 00:44:44,834
And, Mr. Burnett,
you can certainly help.

621
00:44:44,920 --> 00:44:47,514
Don't just stand there.
Do as she says.

622
00:44:48,480 --> 00:44:50,516
[Soft instrumental music]

623
00:45:02,080 --> 00:45:03,433
He's got a busted arm...

624
00:45:03,520 --> 00:45:05,909
a bunch of cracked ribs,
l don't know what else.

625
00:45:06,080 --> 00:45:08,799
All we can do
under these primitive conditions...

626
00:45:08,880 --> 00:45:10,472
is to keep him down and hope.

627
00:45:10,560 --> 00:45:11,834
l'm sorry about the place.

628
00:45:11,960 --> 00:45:13,473
[Thunder rumbling]

629
00:45:14,760 --> 00:45:17,593
l'll need something for that roof
to keep the weather out.

630
00:45:17,680 --> 00:45:19,591
l've taken care of that.

631
00:45:23,720 --> 00:45:24,835
You have?

632
00:45:24,920 --> 00:45:27,434
l told that Estaban to fix....

633
00:45:32,040 --> 00:45:34,759
Undisciplined and shiftless,
the whole lot of them.

634
00:45:35,760 --> 00:45:38,194
Yes, but we don't know
that about Jamie, do we?

635
00:45:38,280 --> 00:45:39,349
[Banging on door]

636
00:45:40,920 --> 00:45:41,909
You need this, <i>señora?</i>

637
00:45:42,000 --> 00:45:44,150
No, not in here. Up on the roof.

638
00:45:44,280 --> 00:45:47,511
l don't want to catch the rain,
l want to keep it out.

639
00:45:47,680 --> 00:45:50,513
And pass the information
on to those who ought to know...

640
00:45:50,640 --> 00:45:53,313
that cleanliness
is next to godliness.

641
00:46:05,960 --> 00:46:07,393
[Soft instrumental music]

642
00:46:07,480 --> 00:46:09,755
No, we don't know
about Jamie at all.

643
00:46:17,400 --> 00:46:19,277
[Sober instrumental music]

644
00:46:45,160 --> 00:46:46,752
Will they be gone very long?

645
00:46:46,840 --> 00:46:48,796
Maybe four, five days, maybe more.

646
00:46:49,000 --> 00:46:50,877
<i>There is much work to do.</i>

647
00:46:54,400 --> 00:46:56,072
There certainly is.

648
00:47:30,960 --> 00:47:33,394
That woman has taken over my fort.

649
00:47:33,640 --> 00:47:35,073
Right there.

650
00:47:42,240 --> 00:47:45,312
The entire place
stinks of laundry soap.

651
00:47:46,800 --> 00:47:50,156
Madam, if you do not care
to get snowed in...

652
00:47:50,240 --> 00:47:53,516
l suggest that you hitch up
your wagon and head for Dodge.

653
00:47:53,600 --> 00:47:57,434
l don't intend to head for anywhere
until Jamie recovers.

654
00:47:57,520 --> 00:47:58,999
l'm glad to hear it.

655
00:48:00,480 --> 00:48:01,754
[Dog barking]

656
00:48:02,800 --> 00:48:04,995
He's feeling better
if you care to know.

657
00:48:05,080 --> 00:48:06,877
And furthermore, we can't leave...

658
00:48:06,960 --> 00:48:10,236
until you understand
how to take care of Vindicator.

659
00:48:11,680 --> 00:48:15,468
Now, tomorrow, l would like
to go out and select some cows.

660
00:48:15,680 --> 00:48:18,877
-Select?
-Yes, for breeding purposes.

661
00:48:19,560 --> 00:48:23,109
Madam, out here
it's the fit that survive...

662
00:48:23,520 --> 00:48:26,239
and if that creature of yours
cannot select his own cows...

663
00:48:26,320 --> 00:48:28,470
he is not fit to live here.

664
00:48:28,960 --> 00:48:31,599
l think it may be a good idea
if you take a wee peek...

665
00:48:31,680 --> 00:48:33,352
at some of these
prospective brides...

666
00:48:33,440 --> 00:48:36,512
you're figuring to match up
with that Hereford of yours.

667
00:48:36,600 --> 00:48:39,478
-That's precisely my intention.
-Good.

668
00:48:40,240 --> 00:48:41,992
You come on the morrow...

669
00:48:42,080 --> 00:48:45,277
and l'll hunt up a longhorn cow
for you...

670
00:48:46,080 --> 00:48:49,470
and then you'll see for yourself
why l think that bull of yours...

671
00:48:49,560 --> 00:48:51,676
will not be the father of a calf.

672
00:48:55,920 --> 00:49:00,038
lt won't be exactly the kind of
a hunt you'd expect, ma'am.

673
00:49:00,240 --> 00:49:03,118
-Here, can l help with this?
-No, thank you, Mr. Burnett.

674
00:49:03,200 --> 00:49:06,192
They're clean.
l'd like to keep them that way.

675
00:49:08,800 --> 00:49:10,677
[Soft instrumental music]

676
00:49:18,360 --> 00:49:20,476
-Beef stew?
-Chicken broth.

677
00:49:22,440 --> 00:49:25,000
Snake broth, gopher broth,
anything but chicken broth.

678
00:49:25,080 --> 00:49:26,593
When do l get to eat?

679
00:49:26,800 --> 00:49:29,155
-l can do that.
-Do it then.

680
00:49:33,560 --> 00:49:36,757
-Sure would like something to chew.
-Chew the spoon.

681
00:49:37,880 --> 00:49:39,871
Hey, you're touchy this morning.

682
00:49:40,200 --> 00:49:41,918
Your father's back.

683
00:49:42,360 --> 00:49:44,715
He goes off for a whole week
without saying goodbye...

684
00:49:44,800 --> 00:49:47,394
then doesn't even stop in
to see how you are.

685
00:49:47,520 --> 00:49:48,919
What's between you two?

686
00:49:49,120 --> 00:49:52,351
You snarl and growl at each other
like two wounded animals.

687
00:49:52,440 --> 00:49:53,714
lt's always been like that.

688
00:49:53,800 --> 00:49:56,394
-But why?
-Hilary, don't get involved.

689
00:49:58,760 --> 00:50:00,478
Don't get involved?

690
00:50:01,960 --> 00:50:05,509
Jamie Bowen, if you didn't have
enough broken bones...

691
00:50:05,600 --> 00:50:08,114
l'd certainly
add to your collection.

692
00:50:08,680 --> 00:50:10,989
l'm surrounded by stubbornness.

693
00:50:11,080 --> 00:50:13,799
Sam, Mother, your father,
and now you.

694
00:50:14,640 --> 00:50:17,552
The only one l can talk to
around here is Vindicator.

695
00:50:18,520 --> 00:50:21,353
l hate family mysteries.
Why does it have to be that way?

696
00:50:21,440 --> 00:50:22,873
l don't know!

697
00:50:25,840 --> 00:50:28,354
lf l knew, l'd tell you,
but l don't.

698
00:50:29,040 --> 00:50:30,996
[Soft instrumental music continues]

699
00:50:36,440 --> 00:50:39,716
-l'm sorry.
-That's all right.

700
00:50:40,800 --> 00:50:44,475
You're gonna stay around until l'm
back on my feet again, aren't you?

701
00:50:44,920 --> 00:50:46,990
Maybe even a little longer.

702
00:50:51,240 --> 00:50:54,596
Hilary, we're going out
to select some cows tomorrow.

703
00:50:55,680 --> 00:50:56,954
Jamie, how are you?

704
00:50:57,120 --> 00:50:59,190
Fine, Mrs. Evans.

705
00:50:59,280 --> 00:51:02,397
l just had the best chicken broth
you ever tasted.

706
00:51:03,360 --> 00:51:06,591
But if you find a loose cow
and could slip it past Hilary...

707
00:51:06,680 --> 00:51:09,433
l'd eat it horns, hooves,
hide, everything.

708
00:51:12,040 --> 00:51:13,951
[Lively instrumental music]

709
00:51:16,440 --> 00:51:17,839
[Dogs barking]

710
00:51:38,600 --> 00:51:39,555
[Men yelling]

711
00:51:53,440 --> 00:51:54,793
[Longhorn bellowing]

712
00:52:17,920 --> 00:52:20,878
BOWEN: You still think that bull of yours
could be her mate?

713
00:52:21,280 --> 00:52:24,352
Mr. Bowen, Vindicator's
first calves...

714
00:52:24,480 --> 00:52:27,756
will weigh half again as much
as your longhorn calves...

715
00:52:27,840 --> 00:52:29,273
and they'll be hardy.

716
00:52:29,360 --> 00:52:31,715
She can rip him to tatters
while he's still dancing.

717
00:52:31,800 --> 00:52:34,837
-He'll never beget a calf.
-You're mistaken.

718
00:52:35,320 --> 00:52:37,834
BOWEN: Madam, l've lived half my life here.

719
00:52:38,040 --> 00:52:40,634
And l tell you,
if the longhorns do not kill him...

720
00:52:40,720 --> 00:52:42,836
then the wolves
and the winters will.

721
00:52:43,680 --> 00:52:45,272
And l suppose you agree with him?

722
00:52:45,360 --> 00:52:47,794
Sometimes it gets down
to 20 below, ma'am.

723
00:52:47,880 --> 00:52:49,791
You can see that beast, Mother.

724
00:52:49,920 --> 00:52:51,399
[Bellowing]

725
00:52:51,480 --> 00:52:53,232
A cow? Good Lord!

726
00:52:55,800 --> 00:52:58,394
l believe that Vindicator
will live long enough...

727
00:52:58,480 --> 00:53:00,755
on the open range to reproduce.

728
00:53:00,920 --> 00:53:03,309
And that's all we can expect of him.

729
00:53:04,240 --> 00:53:05,719
Mother, that's cruel.

730
00:53:06,360 --> 00:53:09,875
Yes, it's cruel,
and stupid, and savage.

731
00:53:10,320 --> 00:53:13,073
But then we live among
savage and stupid people.

732
00:53:13,160 --> 00:53:15,549
And the only way to convince them
is on their own terms.

733
00:53:15,680 --> 00:53:18,069
Survival.
That's all they understand.

734
00:53:18,880 --> 00:53:21,758
We could build a shelter.
Keep him alive that way.

735
00:53:22,480 --> 00:53:25,074
l can keep roses alive
in a hothouse.

736
00:53:25,480 --> 00:53:27,755
And you've got
a hothouse bull, madam.

737
00:53:28,240 --> 00:53:29,753
That's not so.

738
00:53:30,000 --> 00:53:33,470
Vindicator does have stamina
and fighting spirit. He does.

739
00:53:33,560 --> 00:53:35,755
My father bred it into him...

740
00:53:35,840 --> 00:53:39,799
and if he has to risk his life
to prove it to you, then he will.

741
00:53:41,440 --> 00:53:43,396
[Solemn instrumental music]

742
00:53:46,880 --> 00:53:49,348
She'll not turn him loose
after what she's seen here.

743
00:53:49,440 --> 00:53:50,668
Yes, she will.

744
00:53:50,760 --> 00:53:52,478
You forget that my husband died...

745
00:53:52,600 --> 00:53:55,990
trying to bring Herefords here
and prove this very point.

746
00:54:02,160 --> 00:54:04,993
That woman does not
fear a thing, eh, Sam?

747
00:54:05,560 --> 00:54:08,677
Nothing but dishonesty and dirt.

748
00:54:27,000 --> 00:54:29,468
Do you think your ma
has any cold beef in the cupboard?

749
00:54:29,560 --> 00:54:32,120
-Sure, Jamie.
-And my ma has tortillas.

750
00:54:32,200 --> 00:54:33,110
[Horse approaching]

751
00:54:36,800 --> 00:54:40,713
Get out of sight! And, Conchita,
come back later with tortillas.

752
00:54:47,720 --> 00:54:50,473
HlLARY: All right, Vindicator. Come on.

753
00:54:58,480 --> 00:55:00,755
<i>Jamie, you shouIdn't be out here.</i>

754
00:55:01,920 --> 00:55:04,559
l like to see open sky
once in a while.

755
00:55:05,560 --> 00:55:07,551
Where you taking Rosy Red?

756
00:55:08,960 --> 00:55:11,872
-Don't call him that.
-l'm sorry, Hilary.

757
00:55:13,280 --> 00:55:16,636
l'm taking him out,
far out on the range...

758
00:55:17,680 --> 00:55:20,069
and l'm going to leave him there.

759
00:55:21,440 --> 00:55:25,228
There's no point in getting yourself
all upset over an old bull.

760
00:55:25,880 --> 00:55:27,393
Vindicator isn't old.

761
00:55:27,480 --> 00:55:29,914
Well, l mean,
he's an animal not a person.

762
00:55:30,560 --> 00:55:33,028
You are a Bowen, yes, you are.

763
00:55:33,720 --> 00:55:35,517
lnsensitive and hateful.

764
00:55:36,200 --> 00:55:38,634
<i>You don't even know</i>
<i>what this means to me.</i>

765
00:55:38,920 --> 00:55:41,718
You can't understand it
and you never will.

766
00:55:43,200 --> 00:55:44,633
Come on, Vindicator.

767
00:55:46,280 --> 00:55:48,350
[Sober instrumental music]

768
00:56:24,680 --> 00:56:26,477
You go along now, Vindicator...

769
00:56:26,560 --> 00:56:29,233
and don't you come back,
do you hear me?

770
00:56:29,400 --> 00:56:30,674
<i>Go aIong.</i>

771
00:56:37,920 --> 00:56:39,239
[Snorting]

772
00:56:46,200 --> 00:56:50,159
Vindicator, you've got to stand
on your own four feet. l mean it.

773
00:56:51,320 --> 00:56:53,993
You're a British bull
with uncommon good sense...

774
00:56:54,080 --> 00:56:55,798
and fine ancestors.

775
00:56:56,800 --> 00:56:58,950
We've had some fine times together.

776
00:56:59,360 --> 00:57:01,510
<i>Now you've got to prove yourseIf.</i>

777
00:57:01,600 --> 00:57:03,909
And prove that Father was right.

778
00:57:05,200 --> 00:57:06,349
Go on.

779
00:57:11,200 --> 00:57:13,430
[Sentimental instrumental music]

780
00:57:21,480 --> 00:57:22,435
[Bellowing]

781
00:57:34,320 --> 00:57:36,072
She turned him loose.

782
00:57:36,320 --> 00:57:38,993
Your lass has got guts,
l'll grant you that.

783
00:57:42,400 --> 00:57:44,391
l suppose you'll be
going home now, ma'am?

784
00:57:44,480 --> 00:57:47,074
What for?
l mean, what's the rush, Sam?

785
00:57:47,840 --> 00:57:51,549
Mistress Evans could pay us
a wee visit for awhile.

786
00:57:52,120 --> 00:57:55,396
Come summer, you'll see the first
crossbred Herefords on this range.

787
00:57:55,480 --> 00:57:58,278
Sam, there's no sense
in telling her a lie.

788
00:57:59,160 --> 00:58:01,310
This is longhorn country...

789
00:58:01,880 --> 00:58:05,475
and it'll stay longhorn country,
madam, you cannot change it.

790
00:58:09,280 --> 00:58:11,032
l meant what l said.

791
00:58:12,200 --> 00:58:14,316
lf only l could believe that,
Mr. Burnett...

792
00:58:14,400 --> 00:58:16,152
it might make a difference.

793
00:58:16,960 --> 00:58:19,599
But l made that mistake once,
didn't l?

794
00:58:19,800 --> 00:58:22,030
Martha, what l did was wrong.

795
00:58:23,240 --> 00:58:27,472
l lied to you because l didn't want
you and Hilary to turn against me...

796
00:58:27,600 --> 00:58:28,999
and l'm sorry.

797
00:58:34,160 --> 00:58:36,071
[Soft instrumental music]

798
00:58:40,960 --> 00:58:43,315
l think l'd better go to Hilary.

799
00:58:49,320 --> 00:58:51,550
Then you're not still mad at me?

800
00:58:51,720 --> 00:58:53,711
No, not particularly.

801
00:58:57,840 --> 00:58:58,989
You know, Jamie...

802
00:58:59,080 --> 00:59:01,958
there's really nothing
to keep us here anymore, is there?

803
00:59:02,040 --> 00:59:04,110
Vindicator's out there
on the range...

804
00:59:04,320 --> 00:59:06,834
-and you're up and around.
-No, now, wait a minute.

805
00:59:06,920 --> 00:59:09,514
l've still got cracked ribs
and they hurt like the devil.

806
00:59:09,600 --> 00:59:11,397
Here, l'll show you.

807
00:59:12,520 --> 00:59:14,909
See? That's painful.
l need attention.

808
00:59:15,400 --> 00:59:17,277
Jamie, you're breaking my ribs.

809
00:59:17,360 --> 00:59:18,349
Yeah.

810
00:59:18,720 --> 00:59:22,793
And l will, too, if that's what
it's gonna take to keep you here.

811
00:59:28,200 --> 00:59:31,590
Look, all l've got is the two legs
l stand on, Hilary...

812
00:59:32,280 --> 00:59:36,114
but there's room in this country to
make us a place like Herefordshire.

813
00:59:36,400 --> 00:59:38,516
l don't care what it's like.

814
00:59:38,600 --> 00:59:40,909
l don't ever want to leave you.

815
00:59:42,200 --> 00:59:44,316
[Romantic instrumental music]

816
01:00:28,840 --> 01:00:30,319
[Wind howling]

817
01:00:32,600 --> 01:00:34,716
BOWEN: [Singing] <i>I'II take the Iow road</i>

818
01:00:35,280 --> 01:00:38,511
<i>I'II be in ScotIand afore ye</i>

819
01:00:47,000 --> 01:00:48,228
<i>Come on!</i>

820
01:00:55,680 --> 01:00:57,716
<i>Get on, wiII you?</i>
<i>I don't need witnesses.</i>

821
01:00:57,800 --> 01:01:00,075
<i>Get out of here! Go, wiII you?</i>

822
01:01:06,720 --> 01:01:08,278
[Bowen continues singing]

823
01:01:09,120 --> 01:01:10,075
[Yelps]

824
01:01:28,520 --> 01:01:31,398
Don't just stand there, man,
slam the door!

825
01:01:36,760 --> 01:01:39,274
SAM: What're you doing?
BOWEN: What does it look like?

826
01:01:39,360 --> 01:01:41,874
You look like a bull
in a mud wallow.

827
01:01:42,400 --> 01:01:45,392
Look, we got a blizzard
on our hands out there.

828
01:01:45,520 --> 01:01:48,751
-The glass is still dropping.
-That's grand.

829
01:01:48,840 --> 01:01:50,671
She'll not be able to travel
in such weather.

830
01:01:50,760 --> 01:01:53,035
Been wondering how to keep her here
short of violence.

831
01:01:53,120 --> 01:01:55,190
How do l smell, Sam?
Do l smell grand now?

832
01:01:55,280 --> 01:01:58,750
-You smell like an old buffalo.
-That's not me, that's the robe.

833
01:01:59,520 --> 01:02:01,954
Alex, l'm going out
and find Vindicator...

834
01:02:02,040 --> 01:02:04,634
and bring him back here
until this weather lets up.

835
01:02:04,800 --> 01:02:08,349
-Let nature take its course, man.
-But l can save him.

836
01:02:08,680 --> 01:02:10,318
BOWEN: Who wants to save him?

837
01:02:10,400 --> 01:02:11,594
After he's no more here...

838
01:02:11,680 --> 01:02:14,752
Mistress Evans will see
that l was right about this place...

839
01:02:15,080 --> 01:02:16,593
and then she may get
a wee glimmer...

840
01:02:16,680 --> 01:02:19,035
that l can be right about
some other things.

841
01:02:19,120 --> 01:02:22,635
Well, it doesn't take any brains
to let a bull die in a blizzard.

842
01:02:23,240 --> 01:02:25,959
Aye, but it takes a great deal
to turn loose of the past...

843
01:02:26,040 --> 01:02:28,349
and that's exactly
what l want her to do.

844
01:02:28,440 --> 01:02:31,750
l want her to forget all about
Herefords, and think about me.

845
01:02:33,240 --> 01:02:34,958
l made up my mind.

846
01:02:35,400 --> 01:02:37,595
l'm going to wed that woman.

847
01:02:38,720 --> 01:02:41,109
-You're going to wed her?
-Aye.

848
01:02:42,640 --> 01:02:45,791
But, Bowen, Mrs. Evans is a lady.
She's an English lady.

849
01:02:45,880 --> 01:02:47,393
She didn't come
all the way out here...

850
01:02:47,480 --> 01:02:49,914
to marry
an old grizzly bear like you.

851
01:02:50,000 --> 01:02:51,718
BOWEN: Yeah, she will, l tell you.

852
01:02:52,200 --> 01:02:55,795
Once that bull is dead and gone,
she'll turn her attention to me:

853
01:02:55,920 --> 01:02:57,512
<i>AIexander Bowen!</i>

854
01:02:58,240 --> 01:02:59,195
[Bowen laughs]

855
01:03:02,080 --> 01:03:05,152
[Singing] <i>Every Iaddie has his Iassie</i>

856
01:03:10,680 --> 01:03:13,956
<i>And aII the girIs they smiIe at me</i>

857
01:03:14,040 --> 01:03:16,235
<i>Coming through the rye</i>

858
01:03:19,760 --> 01:03:22,672
SAM: Anything?
JUAN: That bull has vanished, <i>señor.</i>

859
01:03:23,040 --> 01:03:24,473
lf he's smart like you say...

860
01:03:24,560 --> 01:03:27,393
he headed for the Gulf of Mexico
last week.

861
01:03:27,560 --> 01:03:29,994
A man cannot find a thing
in this snow.

862
01:03:30,080 --> 01:03:32,116
Listen close. Listen.

863
01:03:33,440 --> 01:03:35,351
[Whistles patriotic tune]

864
01:03:38,360 --> 01:03:39,713
You try it.

865
01:03:40,880 --> 01:03:42,552
[Both whistle same tune]

866
01:03:46,800 --> 01:03:49,633
Keep it up loud.
We'll make another swing.

867
01:03:51,520 --> 01:03:52,873
[Wolf howling]

868
01:03:58,600 --> 01:04:00,511
[Sober instrumental music]

869
01:04:03,440 --> 01:04:05,510
Sam, tomorrow l'm going with you.

870
01:04:05,600 --> 01:04:06,999
No, you're not well enough.

871
01:04:07,080 --> 01:04:09,594
l've been doing cartwheels
for weeks.

872
01:04:10,000 --> 01:04:12,560
<i>HiIary and Mrs. Evans are worried</i>
<i>haIf to death about you.</i>

873
01:04:12,640 --> 01:04:14,312
SAM: lt's your job to stop their worrying.

874
01:04:14,400 --> 01:04:16,789
<i>Come on</i>,
<i>Iet's get in out of the coId.</i>

875
01:04:19,680 --> 01:04:21,636
[Tense instrumental music]

876
01:04:22,840 --> 01:04:24,319
[Wolves growling]

877
01:05:01,440 --> 01:05:03,351
[Whistles patriotic tune]

878
01:05:08,440 --> 01:05:10,032
[Children singing]

879
01:05:12,320 --> 01:05:16,393
CHlLDREN: <i>Save her victorious</i>

880
01:05:16,680 --> 01:05:20,639
<i>Happy and gIorious</i>

881
01:05:20,880 --> 01:05:22,950
<i>Long to reign</i>

882
01:05:23,040 --> 01:05:24,871
<i>over us</i>

883
01:05:25,040 --> 01:05:27,952
<i>God save the queen</i>

884
01:05:29,000 --> 01:05:30,228
Mistress Evans.

885
01:05:31,800 --> 01:05:34,678
l'm serving tea at about 4:00
this afternoon.

886
01:05:34,760 --> 01:05:37,399
-l wondered if you'd care to come?
-Tea?

887
01:05:37,480 --> 01:05:40,040
Why, thank you very much, Mr. Bowen.

888
01:05:40,480 --> 01:05:43,597
lt could be a nice change for you.
At 4:00, then.

889
01:05:46,600 --> 01:05:50,036
All right, children. Stand up now.
We're going to sing <i>America.</i>

890
01:05:50,200 --> 01:05:51,758
One, two, three.

891
01:05:52,040 --> 01:05:55,794
[Singing] <i>My country, 'tis of thee</i>

892
01:05:56,800 --> 01:05:58,995
Miss Evans, good day to you.

893
01:06:00,360 --> 01:06:02,157
Up and about, are you?

894
01:06:03,480 --> 01:06:05,516
Do you feel sprightly enough
to run off again?

895
01:06:05,600 --> 01:06:08,637
l'm through running.
l'm going to find me my own place.

896
01:06:09,120 --> 01:06:12,157
That sounds easy when you say it,
but it's not.

897
01:06:12,240 --> 01:06:14,037
Life out here is hard, laddie.

898
01:06:14,120 --> 01:06:16,395
Yeah, well, don't do anything
to make it any softer.

899
01:06:16,480 --> 01:06:18,118
What are you referring to?

900
01:06:18,280 --> 01:06:21,397
Like maybe you could build
some sheds for the stock...

901
01:06:21,560 --> 01:06:25,075
and lay in some winter feed
and repair this godforsaken place?

902
01:06:26,360 --> 01:06:28,555
You've been listening
to that wee lassie.

903
01:06:28,640 --> 01:06:29,755
You bet.

904
01:06:29,840 --> 01:06:33,276
And it's the first sense l've heard
in all this part of Texas.

905
01:06:37,520 --> 01:06:40,796
l'm serving tea at 4:00
this afternoon.

906
01:06:41,720 --> 01:06:44,393
You may bring Miss Evans
if you care to.

907
01:06:46,880 --> 01:06:47,835
[Door closing]

908
01:06:53,040 --> 01:06:55,474
The master will join you presently.

909
01:07:03,600 --> 01:07:05,431
My, aren't we formal.

910
01:07:12,360 --> 01:07:13,998
[Bagpipes playing]

911
01:07:35,440 --> 01:07:36,919
A Highland officer?

912
01:07:37,840 --> 01:07:40,434
91st Argyle. Foot.

913
01:07:45,200 --> 01:07:47,998
You do not recognise me in uniform,
do you, Jamie?

914
01:07:48,120 --> 01:07:50,634
<i>No, you couIdn't.</i>
<i>You were onIy a wee Iad then.</i>

915
01:07:51,680 --> 01:07:55,309
lt's the first time l've scraped
my face since l left my regiment.

916
01:07:55,400 --> 01:07:57,868
Would you care to pour, Mrs. Evans?

917
01:08:03,360 --> 01:08:06,716
Estaban has made us some scones.
He's quite a good cook.

918
01:08:21,160 --> 01:08:23,071
Estaban, you scoundrel.

919
01:08:25,440 --> 01:08:28,637
l thought you were 100 years
older than Sam.

920
01:08:29,440 --> 01:08:31,510
Approve of the change, do you?

921
01:08:31,600 --> 01:08:33,318
The trouble with appearances,
Mr. Bowen...

922
01:08:33,400 --> 01:08:35,231
is while beauty is skin deep...

923
01:08:35,600 --> 01:08:38,068
meanness runs all the way through.

924
01:08:39,080 --> 01:08:40,593
What's that you're saying?

925
01:08:40,680 --> 01:08:42,591
She's saying
that bagpipes and tea...

926
01:08:42,680 --> 01:08:45,069
don't erase the way
you've treated Jamie.

927
01:08:45,320 --> 01:08:47,595
l did the best l could, lassie.

928
01:08:49,760 --> 01:08:54,117
And l could not help it if he
did not have a mother's tender care.

929
01:08:56,120 --> 01:08:58,839
All these years
you've hardly ever spoken to him.

930
01:08:58,920 --> 01:09:01,639
lt does not suit my purpose
to discuss the past.

931
01:09:01,840 --> 01:09:03,876
-You mean my mother?
-Aye.

932
01:09:06,400 --> 01:09:09,198
Now, what could l have
said to you, Jamie?

933
01:09:09,680 --> 01:09:12,194
She was ailing when you were born...

934
01:09:13,600 --> 01:09:15,079
and she died.

935
01:09:17,680 --> 01:09:21,195
<i>And aII the words in the worId</i>
<i>cannot bring her back...</i>

936
01:09:22,760 --> 01:09:24,398
or your husband.

937
01:09:26,640 --> 01:09:27,914
Mistress Evans...

938
01:09:28,000 --> 01:09:31,629
you've captured my entire fort
and all of its inhabitants.

939
01:09:32,560 --> 01:09:35,438
You've got them eating
out of your wee hand.

940
01:09:37,400 --> 01:09:38,799
Aye, it's true.

941
01:09:39,240 --> 01:09:42,198
Now you've made attachments here
yourself, dear lady.

942
01:09:42,760 --> 01:09:45,399
<i>To Jamie</i>
<i>and to the schooIchiIdren....</i>

943
01:09:46,480 --> 01:09:49,552
l just wish.... l mean...

944
01:09:49,920 --> 01:09:53,515
l've been hoping that you could
find it in your heart to...

945
01:09:54,080 --> 01:09:56,514
make a similar attachment to me.

946
01:09:57,680 --> 01:09:59,591
[Soft instrumental music]

947
01:10:01,000 --> 01:10:03,036
Given a wee while, of course.

948
01:10:03,120 --> 01:10:05,270
l wouldn't want to rush you.

949
01:10:06,680 --> 01:10:10,673
And l want you to think about
making your home here in Texas.

950
01:10:11,360 --> 01:10:13,078
You and your lassie.

951
01:10:14,040 --> 01:10:16,873
She likes it here
by the looks of things.

952
01:10:18,800 --> 01:10:20,233
<i>What I'm trying to say...</i>

953
01:10:20,320 --> 01:10:23,357
is that could be such a grand life
for us all.

954
01:10:26,600 --> 01:10:28,750
lt would never be
like Herefordshire.

955
01:10:28,840 --> 01:10:31,593
Aye, and it's not
like Scotland, either.

956
01:10:32,320 --> 01:10:35,596
But when l first came here,
l made up my mind...

957
01:10:36,160 --> 01:10:38,310
l was going to accept the land
as l found it.

958
01:10:38,400 --> 01:10:41,756
That's what you must do
because you cannot change it.

959
01:10:42,120 --> 01:10:45,237
And if you're still thinking
that l'm responsible...

960
01:10:45,360 --> 01:10:49,194
because Hereford cattle cannot
adapt themselves to Texas...

961
01:10:49,720 --> 01:10:51,392
and that l shattered...

962
01:10:51,480 --> 01:10:54,950
that lovely dream you shared
with your husband, that's not true.

963
01:10:55,080 --> 01:10:57,230
You cannot live with dreams.

964
01:10:58,320 --> 01:11:01,835
lt's time to stop dreaming
and live for this day...

965
01:11:03,000 --> 01:11:04,592
and the next day.

966
01:11:06,960 --> 01:11:09,997
Time for me to admit
that this is longhorn country...

967
01:11:10,080 --> 01:11:12,514
and that you're its lord and master.

968
01:11:13,840 --> 01:11:18,118
A man in love is not even lord
nor master of himself.

969
01:11:25,360 --> 01:11:28,238
l'd like to change the climate
for you, if l could.

970
01:11:32,880 --> 01:11:34,836
[Tense instrumental music]

971
01:11:36,120 --> 01:11:38,839
What are you looking at, man?

972
01:11:38,920 --> 01:11:40,592
ls that you, <i>Señor</i> Bowen?

973
01:11:41,320 --> 01:11:44,278
No, l'm Bonnie Prince ruddy Charlie.

974
01:11:44,640 --> 01:11:47,200
BOWEN: What do you want?
JUAN: l lost touch with him.

975
01:11:47,640 --> 01:11:49,551
BOWEN: With who?
JUAN: <i>Señor</i> Burnett.

976
01:11:50,400 --> 01:11:52,356
l could hear him whistling,
but he was gone...

977
01:11:52,440 --> 01:11:54,908
l could not find him.
The snow was too heavy.

978
01:11:55,040 --> 01:11:56,155
ls he lost?

979
01:11:56,240 --> 01:11:58,549
No, <i>señora</i>, maybe he has troubles...

980
01:11:59,160 --> 01:12:00,878
but <i>Señor</i> Burnett is not lost.

981
01:12:00,960 --> 01:12:02,837
Fetch the men. Go on with you.

982
01:12:02,920 --> 01:12:05,150
BOWEN: Saddle my horse.
JAMlE: l'll come, too.

983
01:12:06,480 --> 01:12:08,311
Don't worry, we'll find him.

984
01:12:13,800 --> 01:12:15,199
[Wind howling]

985
01:12:15,280 --> 01:12:16,429
[Horse neighing]

986
01:13:00,680 --> 01:13:02,591
[Tense instrumental music]

987
01:13:14,040 --> 01:13:14,995
[Gunshots firing]

988
01:13:53,760 --> 01:13:55,716
[Soft instrumental music]

989
01:14:01,040 --> 01:14:02,234
[Gasping]

990
01:14:06,560 --> 01:14:07,993
l have been wondering for years...

991
01:14:08,080 --> 01:14:10,719
what you were hiding
behind that beard of yours.

992
01:14:11,000 --> 01:14:13,116
l told you before, a man can change.

993
01:14:13,520 --> 01:14:15,556
All right, you've changed.

994
01:14:15,640 --> 01:14:18,757
l'm sure Mrs. Evans approves.
Well, l haven't changed.

995
01:14:19,320 --> 01:14:23,108
That Hereford bull's out here
somewhere and l'm gonna find him.

996
01:14:23,880 --> 01:14:25,598
Do you think you be fit to travel?

997
01:14:25,680 --> 01:14:27,398
Of course l'm fit....

998
01:14:28,440 --> 01:14:29,395
[Groaning]

999
01:14:31,320 --> 01:14:32,275
[Grunts]

1000
01:15:06,640 --> 01:15:08,631
SAM: Quit shoving. l can walk.

1001
01:15:09,880 --> 01:15:12,792
Come over here, Sam.
Hilary, get some coffee.

1002
01:15:13,480 --> 01:15:17,359
l don't want you to go out there
any more, do you understand?

1003
01:15:17,760 --> 01:15:19,990
You think Vindicator's dead, too?

1004
01:15:20,320 --> 01:15:22,754
Yes, but that doesn't matter now.

1005
01:15:23,720 --> 01:15:25,438
No, l'll do this.

1006
01:15:32,440 --> 01:15:35,477
There isn't anything worth
the risk you're taking, Sam.

1007
01:15:36,840 --> 01:15:38,512
-There isn't?
-No.

1008
01:15:39,160 --> 01:15:41,196
This is longhorn country.

1009
01:15:41,440 --> 01:15:44,113
Let's face it and be done with it
once and for all.

1010
01:15:44,200 --> 01:15:46,270
Well, l'm not done with it.

1011
01:15:46,720 --> 01:15:50,679
You planted an idea in me,
Mrs. Evans, and the roots went deep.

1012
01:15:50,760 --> 01:15:54,548
<i>I think Vindicator is as good</i>
<i>or better than any Ionghorn aIive.</i>

1013
01:15:54,960 --> 01:15:58,350
And come summer, there's gonna be
crossbreed Herefords on this range.

1014
01:15:58,440 --> 01:15:59,953
<i>You just wait and see.</i>

1015
01:16:00,880 --> 01:16:02,279
Not on this range.

1016
01:16:02,520 --> 01:16:04,556
Just because you shaved
and took a bath...

1017
01:16:04,640 --> 01:16:06,676
don't be so high and mighty
about everything.

1018
01:16:06,760 --> 01:16:08,671
You don't know Hereford stock.

1019
01:16:09,160 --> 01:16:11,720
Sam Burnett, l give you
my permission...

1020
01:16:11,800 --> 01:16:14,758
to clear the range
of any crossbreed cows you can find.

1021
01:16:14,840 --> 01:16:16,034
<i>Take them. They're yours.</i>

1022
01:16:16,120 --> 01:16:18,315
<i>But do not worry us</i>
<i>about it anymore.</i>

1023
01:16:18,400 --> 01:16:19,879
lt's not good for Mistress Evans...

1024
01:16:19,960 --> 01:16:22,758
to hear you constantly
dragging up the past.

1025
01:16:24,360 --> 01:16:26,430
Besides, l've asked her to wed me.

1026
01:16:26,680 --> 01:16:28,875
<i>And she hasn't exactIy said no.</i>

1027
01:16:32,520 --> 01:16:34,351
Seems to me
like you've broken faith...

1028
01:16:34,440 --> 01:16:36,670
with everything
that brought you here.

1029
01:16:37,200 --> 01:16:40,954
l've never been a person
to avoid facing facts, Mr. Burnett.

1030
01:16:41,560 --> 01:16:43,551
And you should know that.

1031
01:16:44,120 --> 01:16:46,953
l was wrong about this country.
And l admit it.

1032
01:16:47,400 --> 01:16:50,153
Well, then, your husband
was wrong about Herefords, too.

1033
01:16:50,240 --> 01:16:51,992
Yes. All right, yes!

1034
01:16:52,240 --> 01:16:54,151
But there are other things
to consider.

1035
01:16:54,240 --> 01:16:57,198
There's Hilary and Jamie.
And life must go on.

1036
01:17:05,320 --> 01:17:06,992
All right, Alex...

1037
01:17:07,840 --> 01:17:09,956
l'll take
the crossbreed Herefords l find...

1038
01:17:10,040 --> 01:17:11,996
and l'll build a place for them.

1039
01:17:12,120 --> 01:17:14,156
Sam, don't. Can't you see it's over?

1040
01:17:14,240 --> 01:17:15,514
SAM: Not for me.

1041
01:17:17,320 --> 01:17:18,833
Give him a hand.

1042
01:17:23,040 --> 01:17:25,679
He's hell-bent
for disaster out there.

1043
01:17:26,240 --> 01:17:28,196
There's no stopping him.

1044
01:17:30,800 --> 01:17:32,518
[Sober instrumental music]

1045
01:17:32,640 --> 01:17:34,119
[Jamie yelling]

1046
01:17:51,360 --> 01:17:53,396
[Ominous instrumental music]

1047
01:17:56,320 --> 01:17:57,275
[Gunshot firing]

1048
01:18:03,560 --> 01:18:05,073
Jamie, here's Sam.

1049
01:18:16,120 --> 01:18:17,519
You're driving them in, huh?

1050
01:18:17,600 --> 01:18:19,272
Yeah, a lot of them aren't up to it.

1051
01:18:19,360 --> 01:18:21,715
Dad says he can't remember
a worse winter.

1052
01:18:21,800 --> 01:18:24,075
We haven't seen much of you, Sam.
How have you been?

1053
01:18:24,160 --> 01:18:25,639
l'm fine. Fine.

1054
01:18:26,080 --> 01:18:28,389
-Building a place.
-Yeah, Juan was telling me.

1055
01:18:28,480 --> 01:18:31,233
Juan, he comes out
every once in a while, lends a hand.

1056
01:18:31,320 --> 01:18:34,073
-l'd like to see it, Sam.
-Not till it's finished.

1057
01:18:34,280 --> 01:18:37,158
l'm working
on the calving pens now. Waiting.

1058
01:18:42,280 --> 01:18:44,077
l'll be moving along.

1059
01:19:00,920 --> 01:19:01,989
[Neighing]

1060
01:19:13,160 --> 01:19:14,479
[Horse neighing]

1061
01:19:15,520 --> 01:19:16,794
Whoa, boy.

1062
01:19:17,120 --> 01:19:18,997
[Tense instrumental music]

1063
01:20:03,160 --> 01:20:05,196
lt's Vindicator, isn't it?

1064
01:20:09,520 --> 01:20:11,670
A lot of longhorns died, too.

1065
01:20:12,440 --> 01:20:14,237
We knew what to expect, Sam.

1066
01:20:19,000 --> 01:20:21,275
Now, l want you to tell Bowen.

1067
01:20:21,920 --> 01:20:25,879
You tell him that this doesn't mean
there won't be calves.

1068
01:20:29,440 --> 01:20:31,158
You tell him that.

1069
01:20:31,920 --> 01:20:33,558
You tell them both.

1070
01:20:46,360 --> 01:20:48,351
[Solemn instrumental music]

1071
01:22:07,440 --> 01:22:09,271
-Hello, Hilary.
-Hello, Sam.

1072
01:22:09,400 --> 01:22:12,392
-Juan directed me how to get here.
-lt's not hard to find.

1073
01:22:12,480 --> 01:22:15,233
Jamie knows it.
He's been out here lots of times.

1074
01:22:15,520 --> 01:22:19,229
Yes. Jamie and l aren't
on very good terms at the moment.

1075
01:22:19,800 --> 01:22:20,915
l see.

1076
01:22:21,480 --> 01:22:23,869
-Could l talk to you for a bit, Sam?
-Sure.

1077
01:22:25,840 --> 01:22:27,159
HlLARY: Thank you.

1078
01:22:27,560 --> 01:22:31,314
l have some medium-hot coffee
in there. Would you like some?

1079
01:22:31,400 --> 01:22:32,992
HlLARY: Yes, thanks.

1080
01:22:34,960 --> 01:22:36,916
Here, l'll let you
take the real chair.

1081
01:22:37,000 --> 01:22:38,194
HlLARY: Thanks.

1082
01:22:38,400 --> 01:22:40,550
l'm just finishing up the calf pens.

1083
01:22:40,640 --> 01:22:43,074
l built two corrals
up in the canyon.

1084
01:22:45,720 --> 01:22:48,029
Do you still think
there will be calves?

1085
01:22:48,320 --> 01:22:51,278
SAM: Yes, l do.
You see, it's only the end of June.

1086
01:22:51,480 --> 01:22:54,711
Vindicator could have lasted longer
than anybody expected.

1087
01:22:54,840 --> 01:22:57,354
You could see his calves
clear into October.

1088
01:22:58,000 --> 01:22:59,228
l see.

1089
01:23:08,280 --> 01:23:11,033
-What did you say this was, Sam?
-Coffee.

1090
01:23:12,480 --> 01:23:15,233
l'm sorry about you and Jamie.

1091
01:23:15,720 --> 01:23:17,551
You two have a fight?

1092
01:23:17,720 --> 01:23:20,154
That's what
l wanted to talk to you about.

1093
01:23:20,760 --> 01:23:23,354
You see, everything's become
so complicated.

1094
01:23:23,520 --> 01:23:26,398
lt's just that Jamie asked me
to marry him.

1095
01:23:26,480 --> 01:23:28,914
SAM: l think that's fine.
HlLARY: And l said no.

1096
01:23:29,000 --> 01:23:32,151
-You don't love him?
-Yes, l do. Very much.

1097
01:23:32,240 --> 01:23:33,992
-Well, then--
-But don't you see...

1098
01:23:34,080 --> 01:23:37,629
if l marry Jamie then Mother
will have to marry Mr. Bowen.

1099
01:23:39,000 --> 01:23:41,070
No, l'm afraid l don't follow you.

1100
01:23:41,400 --> 01:23:43,550
Sam, don't you ever think
about Mother?

1101
01:23:43,640 --> 01:23:46,359
Think about her?
l think about her all the time.

1102
01:23:46,760 --> 01:23:49,513
l have this place here
and this idea...

1103
01:23:49,600 --> 01:23:52,114
and that's more than l ever had
in my whole life before.

1104
01:23:52,200 --> 01:23:54,350
And your mother
made this all possible for me.

1105
01:23:54,440 --> 01:23:55,873
And it means a lot.

1106
01:23:56,640 --> 01:24:00,110
Then, it's not right for you to
keep all these things to yourself.

1107
01:24:00,200 --> 01:24:02,873
lt's not fair. Mother needs you.

1108
01:24:04,000 --> 01:24:06,958
l'm afraid l'm not very good
at figuring out problems...

1109
01:24:07,040 --> 01:24:08,314
especially other people's.

1110
01:24:08,400 --> 01:24:11,437
All l know is that
l'm tied to this idea here...

1111
01:24:11,600 --> 01:24:14,990
that your mother gave me, and l'm
just bound to go through with it.

1112
01:24:15,440 --> 01:24:17,112
But it'll be too late, Sam.

1113
01:24:17,200 --> 01:24:18,349
Mother and Mr. Bowen--

1114
01:24:18,440 --> 01:24:20,635
No, your mother'll make
her own decision.

1115
01:24:21,000 --> 01:24:22,797
And that's as it should be.

1116
01:24:22,920 --> 01:24:25,480
But you ought to make yours, too,
Hilary.

1117
01:24:26,600 --> 01:24:29,319
lf you love Jamie, l think
you ought to go up and tell him.

1118
01:24:29,400 --> 01:24:30,833
And marry him.

1119
01:24:37,400 --> 01:24:39,914
-Do you think l should?
-l sure do.

1120
01:24:50,840 --> 01:24:52,990
Well, thanks for the coffee.

1121
01:24:53,200 --> 01:24:56,909
-l'm glad l came to see you.
-l'm glad you did, too.

1122
01:25:09,520 --> 01:25:11,078
Come back, Sam.

1123
01:25:20,480 --> 01:25:22,436
[Soft instrumental music]

1124
01:25:37,760 --> 01:25:38,988
[Clearing throat]

1125
01:25:41,640 --> 01:25:43,631
[Lively instrumental music]

1126
01:25:52,720 --> 01:25:55,917
lt's a grand day.
Get out of there, you beast, you.

1127
01:25:56,000 --> 01:25:56,955
[Goat bleating]

1128
01:26:16,400 --> 01:26:17,992
lt's a grand day, Mistress Evans.

1129
01:26:18,080 --> 01:26:20,469
-We've got plans to make.
-How thoughtful of you.

1130
01:26:20,560 --> 01:26:23,233
-What l mean to say is that--
-They're lovely.

1131
01:26:23,320 --> 01:26:25,356
l mean to say it's urgent
that we make haste.

1132
01:26:25,440 --> 01:26:28,477
We ought to be thinking
about setting a time.

1133
01:26:36,160 --> 01:26:38,833
Very well, Alex. September, then.

1134
01:26:40,680 --> 01:26:42,398
Late in September.

1135
01:26:44,040 --> 01:26:47,396
You're not still hoping that
there'll be some crossbreed calves?

1136
01:26:48,440 --> 01:26:51,591
l suppose so.
l can't seem to help myself.

1137
01:26:52,080 --> 01:26:55,152
lt's because that lunatic
is still out there searching.

1138
01:26:55,400 --> 01:26:58,551
He's bound to fail, l tell you.
You see that, don't you?

1139
01:26:58,640 --> 01:27:01,598
Yes, l know. But until September.

1140
01:27:02,440 --> 01:27:06,433
-That's not too much to ask, is it?
-No.

1141
01:27:07,080 --> 01:27:09,389
He'll certainly give up by then.

1142
01:27:09,720 --> 01:27:12,280
l agree. September it is.

1143
01:27:22,200 --> 01:27:23,519
[Sober instrumental music]

1144
01:27:47,120 --> 01:27:48,553
[Calf mooing]

1145
01:27:58,800 --> 01:28:00,711
[Fast-paced instrumental music]

1146
01:28:41,120 --> 01:28:43,395
l'm gonna borrow him
for a little while.

1147
01:28:43,720 --> 01:28:45,312
Don't you worry.

1148
01:29:12,520 --> 01:29:14,431
[All chattering]

1149
01:29:14,960 --> 01:29:16,712
Jamie, there's Sam.

1150
01:29:23,080 --> 01:29:24,832
You got a whiteface.

1151
01:29:46,280 --> 01:29:48,555
This is what
you came here for, Martha.

1152
01:29:48,760 --> 01:29:51,320
There's Hereford crossbreeds
on this range.

1153
01:29:52,040 --> 01:29:54,600
That calf will make a fine
wedding present, Sam.

1154
01:29:54,680 --> 01:29:57,114
l told you l'd be back
when l found a crossbreed.

1155
01:29:57,200 --> 01:29:58,599
There's the first one.

1156
01:29:58,800 --> 01:30:01,473
You take your hand off
that woman, Sam Burnett.

1157
01:30:01,600 --> 01:30:04,717
And there'll be more whiteface
but l'm gonna need you, Martha.

1158
01:30:04,800 --> 01:30:07,234
Did you hear what l said?
l said take your hand off her.

1159
01:30:07,320 --> 01:30:09,197
<i>And you get out of here.</i>

1160
01:30:13,040 --> 01:30:14,871
[People clamouring]

1161
01:30:26,280 --> 01:30:27,554
[Bowen yelling]

1162
01:30:36,720 --> 01:30:37,948
[Screaming]

1163
01:30:45,200 --> 01:30:46,394
[Horse neighing]

1164
01:30:52,080 --> 01:30:53,991
[Sentimental instrumental music]

1165
01:30:59,920 --> 01:31:03,276
-Alex, l....
-l can see for myself, woman.

1166
01:31:05,680 --> 01:31:09,355
That's Hereford country
and you can raise the bloody things.

1167
01:31:10,360 --> 01:31:12,510
Raise them if you can, l say.

1168
01:31:13,560 --> 01:31:15,915
That's just what we're going to do.

1169
01:31:16,000 --> 01:31:17,399
And before we're finished...

1170
01:31:17,480 --> 01:31:20,552
you're gonna see crossbreed
Hereford all over this range.

1171
01:31:21,320 --> 01:31:22,275
[Grunts]

1172
01:31:26,320 --> 01:31:28,390
You can take that one with you.

1173
01:31:28,480 --> 01:31:30,550
[Amusing instrumental music]

1174
01:31:45,000 --> 01:31:47,639
That one looks like
one of the first dozen, Martha.

1175
01:31:47,720 --> 01:31:51,315
l'm glad we kept some longhorns,
Sam, for old times' sake.

1176
01:31:51,680 --> 01:31:52,908
So am l.

1177
01:31:54,360 --> 01:31:56,271
They're getting pretty scarce.

1178
01:31:56,760 --> 01:31:59,035
[Hilary whistling patriotic tune]

1179
01:32:03,120 --> 01:32:05,270
There. Watch that one now.

1180
01:32:08,160 --> 01:32:10,151
Do you still think one of them
will come to you?

1181
01:32:10,240 --> 01:32:11,673
No, not really.

1182
01:32:11,920 --> 01:32:14,514
Sometimes a bit of him
catches my eye.

1183
01:32:14,600 --> 01:32:17,319
l like to think
he's still out there. Somewhere.

1184
01:32:17,680 --> 01:32:19,716
[Lively instrumental music]

1185
01:32:48,200 --> 01:32:49,189
English - SDH

